[Black "Introduction to the French"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense. Typically, with  1...e6  Black aims to challenge White's dominance in the center with ...d7-d5 while setting the stage for counterplay on the flanks. Notoriously solid, the French Defense is often underestimated for its deceptive passivity.  Despite the reputation, it remains a formidable weapon at club level. It has also been wielded by some of chess' greatest strategists, including World Champions such as Mikhail Botvinnik and Tigran Petrosian, as well as the two-time World Championship challenger Viktor Korchnoi.  After years of being somewhat overshadowed by other openings, the French is somewhat making a resurgence back to the world elites. It was featured multiple times at the recent 2024 Candidates Tournament and for the first time since 1978 made its way back to the World Chess Championship in 2023. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nd2
{ For any chess history advocates out there, the Tarrasch Variation was named after Dr. Siegbert Tarrasch, one of the most prevalent players in the early 20th century. The move took off in the 1970s when the 12th World Champion Anatoly Karpov used it for a devastating effect.   Before examining the purpose of Nd2, we must first look at the classic and natural  3.Nc3  . We can enter the Winawer Variation with  3...Bb4  , where Black pins the knight  on c3, and cranks up immediate pressure on e4 that forces White to make a crucial decision about the central tension.  The main line  4.e5  c5  5.a3  Bxc3+  6.bxc3  leads to a tactical battleground with wild complications that understandably aren't everyone's cup of tea.   With this knowledge in mind, let us switch gears to  3.Nd2  .  Like its cousin Nc3, Nd2 defends the e4-pawn and offers some distinct advantages. Most importantly, it does not obstruct our c-pawn, thereby allowing the possibility of c3 to bolster the central pawn on d4. We effectively circumvent the Winawer Variation, as  3...Bb4  can be countered with  4.c3  .  With Nd2, we keep the game flexible and prepare to enter a battleground filled with both insane tactical complications and brilliant strategic maneuvers.   With  3.Nd2  , we now come to an important crossroad for Black. Black can either play  3...Nf6  , provoking  4.e5  , or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  , with the option of capturing  the d5-pawn after  4.exd5  with the queen,  4...Qxd5  , or the pawn,  4...exd5  . }
3... Nf6
{ The most common continuation, leading to what I like to refer to as the 'Closed System' of the Tarrasch. Black provokes the advance  4.e5  and allows White to establish a strong center.  Black's game plan involves smashing through this stronghold with moves like ...c5 and ...f6, aiming to break White’s control and turn the tide. Unfortunately, Black will be massively disappointed with what we have in store for them!   3...c5  is only slightly behind in popularity compared to ...Nf6, when we reach the 'Open System' of the Tarrasch.  With  3...c5  , Black tries to undermine the one  downside to Nd2, which, unlike Nc3, does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately.  4.exd5  exd5  .  Ah, the classical battleground between Karpov and Korchnoi!  The position featured no less than seven times in their 1974 FIDE Candidates Final @@StartBracket@@or should I call it the World Championship...@@EndBracket@@, in which Karpov prevailed by the smallest margin en route to become the 12th World Champion. White will sooner or later capture the pawn on c5, which typically leads to Black having just a single d5-pawn in the center with no e- or c-pawns.  This resulting 'isolated queen's pawn' structure forms the bedrock for intriguing positional battles. While this lone pawn can facilitate aggressive plays and control of central squares, it can also turn into a long-term weakness that becomes more apparent as the game progresses.   4...Qxd5  is an important alternative for Black. By developing the queen this early in the game, Black hopes to pressure the center and swap the c- and d-pawns for White's d- and e-pawns, effectively leaving Black with an extra pawn in the center. However, this positional gain comes at a cost: White can capitalize on Black's exposed queen to accelerate development and attempt to snowball into a formidable attack. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ This aggressive pawn launch will be the focus of our repertoire! White grabs more space and tries to consolidate the mighty center. In the French Defense, Black typically seeks to undermine White's stronghold by targeting the d4 and e5-pawns with moves like ...c5 and ...f6. With both f2-f4 and c2-c3, we are going for the absolute maximum. If we succeed in consolidating our center, the advantage will not be in doubt. }
