1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... exd5
{ This move is arguably one of Black's most reliable options in the French Tarrasch. Our best chance for an advantage will be to eventually capture the pawn on c5, leading to a position where Black has just a single d5-pawn in the center and no e- or c-pawns @@StartBracket@@known as an isolated queen's pawn or IQP for short@@EndBracket@@.  We'll delve into IQPs more thoroughly later, but it is noteworthy that an IQP is a double-edged sword. It's important to keep that pawn under control and limit Black's piece activity. }
5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Nf6
{ According to the online lichess database, this move has been played more than any other moves in this position, even though the move itself is a mistake!   The shortcoming of  6...Nf6  is that unlike  6...Bd6  followed by ...Nge7, it does little to defend the open e-file. }
7. O-O
{ As it turns out, Black doesn't have the luxury of time on their side. With the move Re1+ incoming, Black will likely have to concede a pawn or risk the king being stranded in the center. }
7... Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5
{ Black captures the pawn. However, the tempo wasted with ...Be7 and ...Bxc5 casts uncertainty over Black's king. }
9. Re1+ { Asking Black an awkward question of how to get out of the check. }
9... Be7
{ Moving the dark-squared bishop for a third time in a row is met with a rather unpleasant idea. }
10. Qe2
{ Putting pressure on the e7-bishop, and further delaying Black from castling. }
10... Be6
{ Instead,  10...O-O  is a serious mistake. Now that the king no longer protects  the e7-bishop, White can simply win a piece with  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.Qxe7  . }
11. Nd4
{ Further exploiting Black's troubled king and the poor coordination from the rest of Black's pieces. }
11... Bd7 12. N2b3
{ With the e7-bishop needing constant protection, Black's position is already in dire straits.   The engine is seriously suggesting  12...Kf8  , sidestepping the pin, as Black's best move.  White has everything going for them and can simply continue development with Bf4, h3, and Rad1. }
