[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... exd5
{ This move is arguably one of Black's most reliable options in the French Tarrasch. Our best chance for an advantage will be to eventually capture the pawn on c5, leading to a position where Black has just a single d5-pawn in the center and no e- or c-pawns @@StartBracket@@known as an isolated queen's pawn or IQP for short@@EndBracket@@.  We'll delve into IQPs more thoroughly later, but it is noteworthy that an IQP is a double-edged sword. It's important to keep that pawn under control and limit Black's piece activity. }
5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6
{ Black's best move. Unlike  6...Nf6  , which exposes the e-file after  7.O-O  , Black prepares to bring the king to safety  with ...Bd6, ...Nge7, and ...O-O. }
7. dxc5
{ Now that Black has developed the dark-squared bishop, we can capture the c5-pawn, gaining a tempo in the process. }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O Ne7
{ 8...Nf6  is rather unpleasant thanks to  9.Re1+  , thus putting the knight on a slightly less active square  on e7 is a concession Black must make. }
9. Nb3
{ We reached the main IQP position of the French Tarrasch. An isolated queen's pawn is a rather common occurrence in numerous openings and has rather double-edged characteristics. On one hand, it controls more space and allows pieces to develop actively. On the other hand, the isolated pawn can become a weakness in the long term. In particular, the square in front of it @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@ can serve as a powerful outpost.  Based on these observations, we can conclude that this IQP position slightly favors White. The slight concession of the knight going to e7, coupled with the fact that White is very much ready to control the d4-outpost, both suggest that White has a pleasant time ahead. The IQP is more of a liability than an asset in this regard. }
9... Bd6
{ This is by far Black's most popular reply from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/3P4/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  .  Black manages to keep most pieces on the board, which compensates the d5-IQP with potential complications. The slight downside is the placement of Black's knight to e7 instead of the natural f6. }
10. c3 { Pushing the pawn to c3 allow us to consolidate the d4-outpost. } 10...
O-O 11. Bd3
{ Now that Black has castled and the pin on b5 is no longer in existence, we can relocate our bishop to a much more active diagonal − not to mention we are stopping ...Bg4 tactically. }
11... h6 12. h3 { Primarily played to prevent ...Bg4. } 12... Bf5 13. Re1
{ Since we had already committed h2-h3, our approach against @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2nb4/3p4/8/1NPB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bf5  with g2-g3 makes less sense. Instead, we can put pressure on Black's isolated pawn in a different way. }
13... Qd7 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 15. Kf1
{ Similarly to the idea of g2-g3; by sidestepping the check on h2, we put pressure on the d5-pawn. }
15... Be7 16. Qd3 Rad8 17. Bf4 Bf6 18. Rad1
{ Despite Black's best efforts, they were unable to get rid of the weak pawn on d5. Instead, we have our pieces on optimal squares and can slowly strengthen our position with Qd3-b5 and Nb3-c5. }
