[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Open System 3...c5 4.exd5 Qxd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... Qxd5
{ In my opinion, this is the most critical test for White in the French Tarrasch. While developing the queen early tends to be a disadvantage, here it is somewhat justified because White's knight on d2 prevents Nb1-c3, which would typically harass the queen for tempo.  The knight also blocks White's queen on d1, leaving the d4-pawn vulnerable. On the flip side, we can speedily develop our pieces, and the queen will inevitably be chased around. }
5. Ngf3 cxd4
{ The most natural response. Black won't be able to keep the extra pawn, but at least they can develop rapidly in the time it takes White to recover the pawn. }
6. Bc4 { Attacking the queen and allowing us to develop rapidly. } 6... Qd7
{ This is a tricky move order. As we will see shortly, by placing the queen on d7, Black effectively neutralizes the sting of our b3 setup. }
7. O-O Nc6 8. Nb3 Nf6 9. Qe2
{ Instead of regaining the pawn with  9.Nbxd4  , which works well in lines  involving ...Qd6, here it’s more complicated because the queen on d7 is well-positioned against our typical plan of b3 and Bb2. For example, after  9...Nxd4  10.Nxd4  a6  11.b3?!  b5  ,  unlike with ...Qd6, we no longer have  12.Qf3?  as an option since it loses a piece to  12...Bb7  with the queen on d7 protecting the bishop.   However, with  9.Qe2!?  , we turn the tables by exploiting the fact that the queen  on d7, unlike on d6, doesn't protect the e5-square. This gives us time to regain the pawn through a different plan, starting with Rd1 before capturing on d4. This approach wouldn't have worked against  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3q4/2Bp4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qd6  , as Black would control  the e5-square and be able to play  7.O-O  Nf6  8.Nb3  Nc6  9.Qe2  Be7  10.Rd1  e5  . }
9... a6
{ Black prepares ...b5, aiming to drive the c4-bishop back and slow down White's efforts to regain the d4-pawn. }
10. Rd1 b5 11. Bd3 Bb7
{ 11...Be7  and  11...Bd6  don't hold much value on their own, as Black will eventually need to  play ...Bb7. }
12. a4
{ Interestingly, this position has only appeared once in the master database. Regaining the pawn immediately with  12.Nbxd4  is also an option, as  12...Nxd4  13.Nxd4  Qxd4?  loses due to the discovered attack  14.Bxb5+  .   However, by targeting the b5-pawn with  12.a4!?  , we are opting for a dynamic approach by vacating  the c4-square for our light-squared bishop and gaining control of the d-file with our rook instead. }
12... b4
{ Black opts to keep the queenside closed, but at the expense of weakening the c4-square.   Gaining the bishop pair with  12...Nb4?!  is too risky after  13.Nbxd4  Nxd3  14.Rxd3  , as White has multiples threats  with Nxb5, Nf5, and Ne5. }
13. Bc4 Bd6
{ By placing the bishop on d6, Black hopes to generate pressure on White's kingside with the help of ...Qc7 and the bishops on long diagonals. }
14. Nbxd4 Nxd4 15. Rxd4
{ Once again, the rook on d4 is extremely strong and can be swung to h4 for a devastating attack if Black castles kingside. }
15... Qc7
{ Black tries to escape the pin on the d-file.   Attempting to exploit the discovered attack with  15...Bxf3  16.Qxf3  Bxh2?  fails tragically due to  17.Kxh2  Qxd4  18.Qxa8+  , leaving White with a completely winning position. }
16. Bg5 Be7
{ Black must protect the knight on f6 to safely castle kingside.   However,  16...O-O  invites trouble with  17.Bxf6  gxf6  18.Rad1  , when defending with  18...Rfd8  runs into  19.Bxe6!  fxe6  20.Qxe6+  , regaining the piece and picking up two pawns in the process. }
17. Ne5 O-O 18. Re1 Rad8 19. Rh4
{ With White's pieces gathering storm towards Black's kingside, it is becoming very tough for Black. For instance,  19...h6  allows the brilliant  20.Ng6!?  , and after  20...fxg6  21.Qxe6+  Kh8  22.Qxe7  Qxe7  23.Rxe7  Rd1+  24.Bf1  , White transitions into a winning endgame. }
