1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... Qxd5
{ In my opinion, this is the most critical test for White in the French Tarrasch. While developing the queen early tends to be a disadvantage, here it is somewhat justified because White's knight on d2 prevents Nb1-c3, which would typically harass the queen for tempo.  The knight also blocks White's queen on d1, leaving the d4-pawn vulnerable. On the flip side, we can speedily develop our pieces, and the queen will inevitably be chased around. }
5. Ngf3 cxd4
{ The most natural response. Black won't be able to keep the extra pawn, but at least they can develop rapidly in the time it takes White to recover the pawn. }
6. Bc4 { Attacking the queen and allowing us to develop rapidly. } 6... Qd6
{ The most popular retreat. However, I think  6...Qd7  and  6...Qd8  will both transpose to the main line. For example,  6...Qd7  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Nb3  Nf6  9.Nbxd4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qc7  and we reached our main line. }
7. O-O
{ First, we get our king to safety and avoid any funny businesses involving ...Qb4+.   For instance,  7.Nb3  Qb4+  , when White's best option is to bring the knight  back to d2 with  8.Nbd2  . }
7... Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4
{ This is the main tabiya of the chapter, with more than 2700 master games played to date from the 4500 games after 4...Qxd5. }
10... a6
{ By far the most popular reply. Black prevents Nb5/Bb5+ while simultaneously preparing for ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7, aiming to activate the bishop on the long diagonal. }
11. b3
{ This is the main part of our repertoire against 4...Qxd5.   Instead of the conventional  11.Re1  followed by Bg5, we opt to fianchetto the bishop on b2. This bishop will play a crucial role in controlling the e5-square with potentially Nf3-e5 and can also assist in a kingside attack by targeting the f6-knight with Bxf6. }
11... b5 { Black tries to gain time on the bishop while preparing ...Bb7. } 12.
Qf3
{ That's it! Instead of retreating our bishop back to e2, we can capitalize on Black's loose rook on a8. Here, Black must be extremely careful not to be worse. In fact, in this tight spot, Black has only one move to keep the balance! }
12... Rb8
{ Putting the rook on the same diagonal as the queen is just asking for trouble. }
13. Rd1
{ Before hitting Black with Bf4, we need to first secure our knight.  13.Bf4?  is bad due to  13...Qxd4  14.Bxb8  bxc4  , when Black is doing fine. }
13... bxc4 14. Bf4 Qb6
{ 14...e5  is not much better for Black, as  15.Bxe5  Qxe5  16.Re1  wins the queen. }
15. Bxb8 Qxb8 16. Nc6
{ The looming threat of Rd8# will win Black's queen. Although Black will indeed get three minor pieces for the queen, the king won't survive the incoming onslaught with Rd1+ and Qc6. }
