1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ A waiting move. Black simply develops the bishop and waits for White to show their hands. }
4. c3 c5 5. dxc5
{ Trying to gain a tempo by exploiting Black's early bishop move. } 5... Bxc5
6. Bd3 Nf6
{ Developing the knight and putting pressure on our e4-pawn. Similarly to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  , Black is provoking us to advance our e-pawn with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2bp4/4P3/2PB4/PP1N1PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e5  , after which they will try to pressure it now that it misses the protection  from the d4-pawn. }
7. e5
{ We will advance our pawn anyway! Despite missing our d4-pawn, we will secure the e5-pawn in a different way. }
7... Nfd7 8. f4
{ Similar to 3...Nf6, we want to maximize our space advantage with this consolidating move. With  8.f4  , we are now preparing to complete development  with Ngf3 before occupying the d4-square with Nb3-d4. }
8... Nc6 9. b4
{ Pushing the bishop back in an attempt to doom Black to passivity. } 9... Be7
10. Ndf3 O-O 11. Qc2 { Putting pressure on Black's h7-pawn. } 11... h6
{ Black stops the threat of Bxh7+, but now the h6-pawn may present itself as a focus of White's attack. With an imminent g2-g4-g5, the pawn on h6 will be our target to smash open Black's kingside. }
12. Ne2 a5 13. b5 Ncb8 14. g4
{ As we mentioned earlier, the pawn on h6 opens the possibility for g4-g5xh6, exposing Black's king to a devastating attack. }
14... Nc5 15. g5
{ White has a crushing attack brewing, while it is unclear what Black has achieved in the meantime. }
