[Black "Other 3rd Moves − 3...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6
{ At first, this seems odd and almost counterintuitive. Black voluntarily blocks their own c-pawn, while ...c7-c5 in most positions in the French constitutes Black's most natural and effective counterplay.  Still, this move caught the attention of one of the greatest opening innovators of all time, Aron Nimzowitsch, who played it from time to time. So there is more than meets the eye and this move is not to be overlooked. }
4. Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nd7
{ Black has provoked the e5 advance and prepares for counterplay with ...f6. }
6. c3 f6 7. Bb5
{ A dangerous move. The bishop temporarily ties Black's knights down to the king, hindering Black's counterplay. In the long run, Black will be able to untangle with ...Be7 and ...O-O, but by then White would have also completed development. Additionally, the bishop can also be retreated to d3 later to exert pressure on Black's kingside. }
7... fxe5 8. dxe5 Be7 9. O-O
{ 9.Nd4  is also quite interesting. As this is a sideline, I've chosen not to include it as an alternative. But the point is that  9...Ndxe5  runs into  10.Qh5+  Kf8  11.f4  Nxd4  12.fxe5  Nf5  13.Nf3  and Black's king is certainly attracting some unwanted attention. }
9... O-O 10. Re1
{ If Black's pawn is on c5 instead of c7, Black would already be fine, if not slightly better with the queenside play. Instead, here Black has little to show for 3...Nc6, and instead must spend additional moves moving the knight to achieve ...c5. Black must also be cautious of potential Re1-e3-h3 and Qd1-h5 ideas. }
10... a6
{ A natural move to gain a tempo on the bishop while preparing the advance of queenside pawns. But here Black can easily get in trouble. }
11. Ba4 b5 12. Bc2 Nc5 13. Nd4
{ That's it! The queen is coming to h5 and Black is simply busted. } 13... Bd7
14. Qh5 { White has a crushing attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Closed System 3...Nf6 − Various Tries"]
[Black "Closed System 3...Nf6 4.e5 Ne4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ The most popular continuation, leading to what I like to refer to as the 'Closed System' of the Tarrasch. Black provokes the advance  4.e5  and allows White to establish a strong center.  Black's game plan involves smashing through this stronghold with moves  like ...c5 and ...f6, aiming to break White’s control and turn the tide. Unfortunately, Black will be massively disappointed with what we have in store for them! }
4. e5 Ne4
{ This is a relatively uncommon idea compared to  4...Nfd7  , though it has been tested on multiple occasions by grandmasters like Vladimir Malaniuk, Rafael Vaganian, and Ian Rogers. The main problem with this move is that once White captures the knight  on e4, Black is left with a weak pawn on e4 that will prove difficult to defend. }
5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. Bc4
{ The bishop is ideally placed on c4, where it keeps the option of d4-d5 open. The e4-pawn is a long-term weakness if Black chooses not to strike immediately in the center. }
6... c5 { 6...Nc6  7.c3  Be7  8.Qg4  and White  rounds up the e4-pawn. } 7. d5
{ The idea behind 6.Bc4 − we seek to grab space and dominate the center with our bishop. }
7... exd5 8. Qxd5
{ We are happy to exchange queens here, since it more or less stablizes our light-squared bishop in the centre of the board. Black is going to struggle in this queenless middlegame. }
8... Qxd5 9. Bxd5 Nc6 10. Bxe4
{ By capturing the pawn on e4 and allowing Black to capture on e5, we enable our bishops to take the center stage and dominate the entire board. }
10... Nxe5 11. Bf4 Ng6 12. Bc7
{ White's dark-squared bishop will soon be a thorn in Black's position. We effectively stop Black from contesting for the open d-file with a potential ...Be7, ...O-O, and ...Rd8. }
12... Be7 13. Nf3 O-O 14. O-O-O
{ Despite the material equality, White has a clear edge. White will soon control both of the open files while the bishops roam freely over the board. }
