[White "1) Closed System 3...Nf6 − Various Tries"]
[Black "Closed System 3...Nf6 4.e5 Ne4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ The most popular continuation, leading to what I like to refer to as the 'Closed System' of the Tarrasch. Black provokes the advance  4.e5  and allows White to establish a strong center.  Black's game plan involves smashing through this stronghold with moves  like ...c5 and ...f6, aiming to break White’s control and turn the tide. Unfortunately, Black will be massively disappointed with what we have in store for them! }
4. e5 Ne4
{ This is a relatively uncommon idea compared to  4...Nfd7  , though it has been tested on multiple occasions by grandmasters like Vladimir Malaniuk, Rafael Vaganian, and Ian Rogers. The main problem with this move is that once White captures the knight  on e4, Black is left with a weak pawn on e4 that will prove difficult to defend. }
5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. Bc4
{ The bishop is ideally placed on c4, where it keeps the option of d4-d5 open. The e4-pawn is a long-term weakness if Black chooses not to strike immediately in the center. }
6... a6
{ Instead of striking immediately in the center, Black looks to first gain space on the queenside with ...b5 while protecting the e4-pawn by fianchettoing the bishop to b7. }
7. a4 { It makes sense to stop Black from playing the natural ...b5. } 7... b6
8. Nh3
{ The knight takes an unusual spot on h3, where it can either relocate to g5, targeting the e4-pawn, or to f4, where it supports the d4-d5 push. }
8... Bb7 9. Nf4 Nc6
{ Black develops the knight and puts pressure on our center.   The alternative  9...c5  gives us the opportunity to play  10.d5!  , when White's lead in development starts to become a real factor. After  10...exd5  11.Nxd5  Nc6  12.Bg5!  , White seizes control of the position. Black cannot capture the bishop, as doing so leads to a quick checkmate with  12...Qxg5  13.Nc7+  Ke7  14.Qd6#  . }
10. c3
{ The last few moves have solidified our strong pawn structure. In the meantime, we have effectively shut down Black's key pawn breaks of ...b5, ...c5, and ...f6. }
10... Ne7 11. O-O g6 12. Qb3
{ With  12.Qb3  , White sets up a clever trap. If Black plays the natural  12...Bg7  , we can unleash  13.Bxe6!  fxe6  14.Nxe6  , forking the queen and bishop. White is in a commanding position. }
