[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Closed System 3...Nf6 − Various Tries"]
[Black "Closed System 4...Nfd7 5.f4 b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ The most popular continuation, leading to what I like to refer to as the 'Closed System' of the Tarrasch. Black provokes the advance  4.e5  and allows White to establish a strong center.  Black's game plan involves smashing through this stronghold with moves  like ...c5 and ...f6, aiming to break White’s control and turn the tide. Unfortunately, Black will be massively disappointed with what we have in store for them! }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ That's it! White grabs more space and tries to consolidate the mighty center. In the French, Black's main source of counterplay comes from pressuring the d4 and e5-pawns. With f2-f4 and c2-c3, we are going for the maximum.  ♔ Just remember as a rule of thumb, more space allows more activity from your pieces. You also reduce the scope of your opponent's pieces and can often doom them to passivity.   To better illustrate my point,  5.Bd3  is actually the most popular move and is considered the more positional approach. However, this allows Black to challenge White's pawn center with  5...c5  , followed by  6.c3  Nc6  7.Ne2  cxd4  8.cxd4  f6!?  At this point, White can no longer maintain control  over the d4-e5 center, as  9.f4?  leads to tactical issues after  9...fxe5  10.fxe5  Nxd4!  11.Nxd4  Qh4+  , where Black wins a pawn thanks to the fork, and White's once-dominant center collapses in front of us. }
5... b6
{ A logical idea, Black hopes to trade off the light-squared bishop to relieve this cramped position. More importantly, the exchange of Black's 'bad' French bishop @@StartBracket@@which is usually stuck behind the e6-d5 pawns and never gets to see the light of day@@EndBracket@@ for its counterpart cannot be understated.  However, the lack of immediate pressure on our center means that we can easily consolidate and even look to expand our center right away. }
6. c3 Ba6 7. Bxa6 Nxa6 8. f5
{ I believe this is White's most aggressive try and suits the style of this repertoire well. The simple  8.Nh3  planning for O-O and f4-f5 isn't bad either. After  8...c5  9.O-O  g6  10.Nf3  h5  , White is better, but Black remains very solid. }
8... exf5 9. Qa4 Nb8
{ 9...Qc8  runs into  10.Qc6  and White regains the d5-pawn. } 10. Nh3
{ The knight aims for the f4-square, where it will pressure Black's d5-pawn. }
10... Be7 11. O-O g6 12. Nf4 c6 13. c4
{ 13.g4  fxg4  14.e6  is also possible, when the engine suggests that Black should better part with the knight to avoid being much worse. However, the text move offers a better version of the same scenario with one piece against three pawns −  the pawn on g2 will keep our king safe, while with c4 White also creates new weaknesses on the light squares.   Starting with  13.e6  is less precise, as after  13...Nf6  14.exf7+  Kxf7  15.Nf3  Re8  ,  White has no follow-up and the black king is safe. With c4 and ...dxc4 included, Black has no time for this since Qxc4+ will immediately spell trouble. }
13... dxc4 14. e6
{ Black's pieces are terribly uncoordinated. Not only are the knights getting in each other's way, but Black's king will soon be exposed as well. }
