4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ That's it! White grabs more space and tries to consolidate the mighty center. In the French, Black's main source of counterplay comes from pressuring the d4 and e5-pawns. With f2-f4 and c2-c3, we are going for the maximum.  ♔ Just remember as a rule of thumb, more space allows more activity from your pieces. You also reduce the scope of your opponent's pieces and can often doom them to passivity.   To better illustrate my point,  5.Bd3  is actually the most popular move and is considered the more positional approach. However, this allows Black to challenge White's pawn center with  5...c5  , followed by  6.c3  Nc6  7.Ne2  cxd4  8.cxd4  f6!?  At this point, White can no longer maintain control  over the d4-e5 center, as  9.f4?  leads to tactical issues after  9...fxe5  10.fxe5  Nxd4!  11.Nxd4  Qh4+  , where Black wins a pawn thanks to the fork, and White's once-dominant center collapses in front of us. }
5... c5 6. c3 Nc6
{ Naturally, Black continues development and tries to put pressure on our d4-pawn. }
7. Ndf3
{ It may seem counterintuitive at first for the d2-knight to come to f3 instead of the knight on g1. However, the knight actually obstructs White's natural development on d2 and hinders the defense of the d4-pawn.   For instance, after  7.Ngf3  Qb6  , White is already facing some difficulties defending  the d4-pawn. By bringing the d2-knight to f3, we envision a natural development trajectory with Bd3, Ne2/h3, and O-O. }
7... f6
{ This typical pawn break in the French is less effective here since we have overprotected our e5-pawn with f2-f4. }
8. Bd3 cxd4 9. cxd4 fxe5 10. fxe5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2
{ Unlike the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  line where I advocated for Kf2, here the subtle difference of playing Bd3 @@StartBracket@@instead of g3@@EndBracket@@ is that after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1n2pp/2n1p3/3pP3/1b1P4/3B1N2/PP4PP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Kf2  , there comes  11...Nxd4  12.Nxd4  O-O+  13.Ngf3  Nxe5  14.Bc2  Nxf3  15.Nxf3  Bc5+  16.Ke1  e5  and White's king is stuck in the center against two menacing-looking pawns, not to mention Black's dangerous bishop pair. }
11... Qa5 12. a3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 Na5 15. Rb1
{ A mysterious rook move. Why place our rook behind the b-pawn instead of seizing control of the open files? However,  15.Rc1  Nb3+  is awkward, while @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp1n2pp/4p3/n2pP3/3P4/P2B1N2/1P1K2PP/R5NR w kq - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Rf1  is reserved for  the h1-rook instead. In addition, putting the rook on b1 comes with a very instructive idea, which we will come to present. }
15... Nb6 16. b3
{ This concept of a3+b3 to shun out Black's knight is one to remember. Without the aid of black pawns, the knights cannot find any play on the queenside. }
16... Nc6 17. Ne2
{ Compare the minor pieces from both sides and hopefully, we will agree that White has a very pleasant endgame ahead. }
