8. Bd3 O-O 9. Ne2
{ A caveman-style approach with  9.h4  looks rather fun as well. For example,  9...f5  10.Ng5  Nb6  11.Qh5  h6  12.Qg6!  hxg5  13.hxg5  Qd7  14.Be2  ,  preparing Qh7+ and Bh5+, spells doom for Black. }
9... f5 { Understandably, Black blocks the lethal b1-h7 diagonal. } 10. O-O
cxd4 11. cxd4 Nb6 12. Kh1
{ This is a recurring theme once Black commits to ...f5. White looks to open the g-file for an attack, while the king is tucked safely away on h1. }
12... Bd7 13. Rg1 Be8 14. g4 Nb4 15. Bb1
{ It may seem unusual and awkward to obstruct the a1-rook by placing the bishop on b1, but it is vital to keep White's bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal to keep any attacking chances alive. By covering c2, the bishop also stops any entrance for Black on the c-file, not to mention the b4-knight will be pushed back by a2-a3 next move. }
15... fxg4 16. Rxg4 Bh5 17. Rg3
{ Black's king is surrounded by a dark cloud, as White has a devastating attack brewing with an incoming Qf1-h3. }
