9. Bd3 Be7 10. Nh3 Qb6
{ It is much better for Black to delay kingside castling. White can risk overextending with O-O, Kh1, Rg1, and g4 if Black chooses to castle queenside instead. }
11. Bc2 { The d4-pawn needs to be protected. } 11... Nf8
{ Preparing to meet  12.Rg1  with  12...Ng6  13.g4  Nh4!  , when White's center begins to show signs of weakness. }
12. O-O Bd7 13. a3 a5 14. Rb1
{ We simply protect the b2-pawn, freeing the bishop from its duty. Over the next few moves, we plan to transfer our h3-knight to the stronger c5-square with Be3 and Nh3-f2-d3-c5. }
14... Ng6 15. Be3 O-O 16. Nf2 Rac8 17. Nd3
{ White will follow up Nc5 and potentially pursue the classical g4 thrust with h3, Kh2 and Rg1. }
