10... Nb6 11. O-O Be7
{ Outside of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qb6  , I believe this relatively harmonious setup is Black's best attempt. It is hence no wonder that this is the recommendation of several French repertoires. By postponing castling together with a rapid expansion on the queenside, Black throws the ball to White's court and asks the question of what next. }
12. Qe1
{ I really like this mysterious queen move. The queen is coming to g3 and potentially harnessing the weakened dark squares when Black plays ...g6.   Before we can fully appreciate the purpose of the move, it is worth noting that the direct  12.g4  ,  intending f4-f5, can be met with  12...h5  . The game Motwani-Dolezal, Luxembourg 1990 continued  13.gxh5  Rxh5  14.Ng3  Rh8  15.f5  Nc4  16.fxe6  Bxe6  , when Black's position remains rock solid, while White has to start worrying about the exposed kingside. }
12... Nc4
{ This is a natural move from Black, dominating White's dark-squared bishop and preparing to meet Bxc4 with ...dxc4. }
13. Qg3 g6 14. Bxc4 dxc4 15. a3
{ By exchanging the bishop for the knight, at first it feels like White has made a grave position error. After all, we voluntarily handed Black the control of the d5-outpost, as well as opening the h1-a8 diagonal for Black's light-squared bishop.   However, with our last move  15.a3!  , we made it extremely difficult for Black  to occupy d5 with the ideal piece for an outpost − the knight. Meanwhile, we will complete development ASAP to prepare for the d4-d5 advance. }
15... b5
{ Black prepares for the fight over d5 with ...Na5 and ...Bb7. Black must act fast to prepare for White's imminent d4-d5.   For example,  15...O-O  is already looking dire after  16.Be3  b5  17.f5!  exf5  18.Rad1  and the threat of d4-d5 is more dangerous than ever. }
16. Kh1
{ Prophylaxis is the key! First, we sidestep our king from any potential nasty checks with ...Bc5+ after d5 or ...Nxd4-e2+. }
16... Na5 17. Be3 Bb7 18. Nc3 Nb3 19. Rad1
{ White is ready for the decisive d4-d5 advance, whereas Black's knight on b3 seems rather misplaced.   One interesting engine line runs  19...Qd7  20.d5!  exd5  21.e6!  Qxe6  22.f5  Qxe3  23.Rfe1  Qc5  24.Rxe7+  Kxe7  25.Qe5+  Kd7  26.Nxd5  Rhd8!!  27.Ne7+  Ke8  28.Nd5+  , with a draw by repetition. }
