{ With the threat of Nxf7 lingering, defending g6 makes sense. The knight could also move to f5. }
13. O-O Nf5 14. c4
{ This move rather reminisces of the wisdom I remembered fondly in my junior days, which was to open up the position when your opponent's pieces are underdeveloped. With c3-c4, we are looking to punish Black for neglecting the development of the bishops, and more importantly, the vulnerable king that is still in the centre. Black is in big trouble now. }
14... dxc4 15. Bxf5 gxf5 16. d5
{ White's dominating knight on g5 combined with the potential passed d-pawn makes a sharp contrast with Black's helpless bishops. }
