8. h4
{ As we see underneath, most of White's moves contain certain downsides. Instead,  8.h4!  stands out as an aggressive and non-committal choice. It not only helps White control more space on the kingside but also sets up the future possibility of advancing the pawn  from h4 to h5 to start an attack.   8.Bd3?  simply blocks the  protection of the d4-pawn. After  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qxd4  ,  White ends up losing an important pawn in the center and, even more importantly, loses the initiative, as Black can now freely continue with ...Bc5. White's attempt to play Bd3 is logical but falls short tactically since with the knight on d7, there is no discovered check on b5.   8.g3  is not a bad choice. White strengthens the mighty pawn chain and offers an alternative spot for the bishop  at h3.  8...Be7  9.Bh3  cxd4  10.cxd4  O-O  11.Ne2  f6!?  A rather intriguing pawn sacrifice where Black aims to open lines and create dynamic play. Chances are about even in the resulting complications.   8.Ne2  f6  , the position has transposed to a variation in the French  Steinitz, Nce2 line, arising after 3.Nc3. My biggest concern is still the light-squared bishop, which struggles to find a significant impact.   8.a3!?  White focuses on preventing Black's play on the queenside before planning an advance on the kingside. This move was recommended in  Christof Selecki's Keep it Simple 1.e4 course and was initially my top choice too. Upon closer inspection, however, I believe Black can achieve decent counterplay thanks to a rapid expansion on the queenside anyway. This move definitely deserves merits, but with 8.h4 we will first keep our options open and only play a2-a3 when it is preferable.  8...a5  9.b3!?  A creative approach to stop Black's pawn advance on the queenside.  White plans to counter ...a5-a4 with b3-b4, slowing Black's queenside momentum.  9...Be7  10.h4  Qc7!?  11.Rb1   11.Bd3  seems logical but ends up being a tactical error after  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  Nxd4  13.Nxd4  Qc3+  , forking the bishop and rook. The author himself may have learned this nasty tactic the hard way...  11...Nb6  12.Bd3  cxd4  13.cxd4  a4  14.Ne2  . @@StartBracket@@After  14.b4  Bd7  ,  preparing ...Na7 and ...Bb5, Black's position looks alright as well.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pq1bppp/1nn1p3/3pP3/p2P1P1P/PP1B1N2/4N1P1/1RBQK2R b Kkq - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...axb3  15.Rxb3  Nc4  16.O-O  g6  and  with the pawns on e6 and g6 firmly stopping White from playing f4-f5, Black finds good counterplay against White's queenside structure without exposing their king to danger. }
8... a5 9. Kf2
{ Going for somewhat of a Bongcloud and voluntarily giving up the rights to castling may seem bizarre at first, but the rationale behind the move is similar to the one with @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h4  .  Black's moves have been aimed at restricting the development of our minor pieces.  Therefore, we must stay patient and minimize Black's initiative before launching our counterpunch. After all, our space advantage with the d4-e5-f4 pawn chain is preventing Black's pieces from mounting any significant attack. By putting our king on f2, we sidestep any ...cxd4 and ...Bb4 business.   The option  9.a4!?  initially seemed appealing. Even though it gives up  the b4-square following ...cxd4, it looked like it might stop Black's counterplay on the queenside and allow White to mount a strong attack on the kingside. However, it turns out that Black can use the blockaded queenside to their advantage and create a safe haven for the king.   After  9...Ndb8  10.h5  cxd4  11.cxd4  Bd7  12.Ne2  Na6  13.Kf2  O-O-O  14.Rh3  Kb8  , Black has untangled most of their pieces and faces no particular problems  with ...Nab4 coming. In any case, this idea of a2-a4 carries some venom especially if Black decides to castle kingside. }
9... Be7 10. h5
{ By expanding on the kingside, White strongly discourage Black from castling there. }
10... a4 11. g4
{ It might seem odd to push all the pawns forward at first. However, moving the g-pawn gives White options like 'manually castling' the king by moving to g2 @@StartBracket@@and maybe the rook to h2 and the king to h1 later@@EndBracket@@, which keeps the king safe. This pawn push also raises questions about the safety of Black's king. }
11... a3 12. b3
{ Since Black's pieces are aiming to break through on the queenside, it only makes sense to keep that side of the board locked up. }
12... Qa5 13. Bd2 b5 14. Rc1 b4 15. cxb4 Nxb4 16. Kg2
{ With the king fairly safe on g2, White has a pleasant position. We will continue our development with Ne2, and prepare for f4-f5.   After  16...Bb7  17.Ne2  Qb6  18.Bxb4  Qxb4  19.f5  , White's kingside pawns may look overextended, but Black has no concrete way of exploiting this. Meanwhile, Black's king doesn't have a safe place to go. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Closed System 3...Nf6 − 7...Qb6"]
[Black "Closed System 7...Qb6 8.h4 cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ The most popular continuation, leading to what I like to refer to as the 'Closed System' of the Tarrasch. Black provokes the advance  4.e5  and allows White to establish a strong center.  Black's game plan involves smashing through this stronghold with moves  like ...c5 and ...f6, aiming to break White’s control and turn the tide. Unfortunately, Black will be massively disappointed with what we have in store for them! }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ That's it! White grabs more space and tries to consolidate the mighty center. In the French, Black's main source of counterplay comes from pressuring the d4 and e5-pawns. With f2-f4 and c2-c3, we are going for the maximum.  ♔ Just remember as a rule of thumb, more space allows more activity from your pieces. You also reduce the scope of your opponent's pieces and can often doom them to passivity.   To better illustrate my point,  5.Bd3  is actually the most popular move and is considered the more positional approach. However, this allows Black to challenge White's pawn center with  5...c5  , followed by  6.c3  Nc6  7.Ne2  cxd4  8.cxd4  f6!?  At this point, White can no longer maintain control  over the d4-e5 center, as  9.f4?  leads to tactical issues after  9...fxe5  10.fxe5  Nxd4!  11.Nxd4  Qh4+  , where Black wins a pawn thanks to the fork, and White's once-dominant center collapses in front of us. }
5... c5 6. c3 Nc6
{ Naturally, Black continues development and tries to put pressure on our d4-pawn. }
7. Ndf3
{ It may seem counterintuitive at first for the d2-knight to come to f3 instead of the knight on g1. However, the knight actually obstructs White's natural development on d2 and hinders the defense of the d4-pawn.   For instance, after  7.Ngf3  Qb6  , White is already facing some difficulties defending  the d4-pawn. By bringing the d2-knight to f3, we envision a natural development trajectory with Bd3, Ne2/h3, and O-O. }
7... Qb6
{ This is the most popular response. Black goes after White's d4-pawn and keeps an eye on the b2-pawn, which makes it more difficult for White to develop the light-squared bishop on its ideal square, d3.   It's important to understand Black's key ideas here. Black may follow up with ...f6, aiming to erode White's strong center by playing ...fxe5, creating immediate counterplay. This can be combined with quick development moves like ...Be7 and ...O-O. Additionally, the queen on b6 is well-positioned to pin White's king on g1, should White castle kingside.   In essence, with  7...Qb6  , Black asks a tough question: How will White continue developing their pieces under this mounting pressure? }
8. h4
{ As we see underneath, most of White's moves contain certain downsides. Instead,  8.h4!  stands out as an aggressive and non-committal choice. It not only helps White control more space on the kingside but also sets up the future possibility of advancing the pawn  from h4 to h5 to start an attack.   8.Bd3?  simply blocks the  protection of the d4-pawn. After  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qxd4  ,  White ends up losing an important pawn in the center and, even more importantly, loses the initiative, as Black can now freely continue with ...Bc5. White's attempt to play Bd3 is logical but falls short tactically since with the knight on d7, there is no discovered check on b5.   8.g3  is not a bad choice. White strengthens the mighty pawn chain and offers an alternative spot for the bishop  at h3.  8...Be7  9.Bh3  cxd4  10.cxd4  O-O  11.Ne2  f6!?  A rather intriguing pawn sacrifice where Black aims to open lines and create dynamic play. Chances are about even in the resulting complications.   8.Ne2  f6  , the position has transposed to a variation in the French  Steinitz, Nce2 line, arising after 3.Nc3. My biggest concern is still the light-squared bishop, which struggles to find a significant impact.   8.a3!?  White focuses on preventing Black's play on the queenside before planning an advance on the kingside. This move was recommended in  Christof Selecki's Keep it Simple 1.e4 course and was initially my top choice too. Upon closer inspection, however, I believe Black can achieve decent counterplay thanks to a rapid expansion on the queenside anyway. This move definitely deserves merits, but with 8.h4 we will first keep our options open and only play a2-a3 when it is preferable.  8...a5  9.b3!?  A creative approach to stop Black's pawn advance on the queenside.  White plans to counter ...a5-a4 with b3-b4, slowing Black's queenside momentum.  9...Be7  10.h4  Qc7!?  11.Rb1   11.Bd3  seems logical but ends up being a tactical error after  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  Nxd4  13.Nxd4  Qc3+  , forking the bishop and rook. The author himself may have learned this nasty tactic the hard way...  11...Nb6  12.Bd3  cxd4  13.cxd4  a4  14.Ne2  . @@StartBracket@@After  14.b4  Bd7  ,  preparing ...Na7 and ...Bb5, Black's position looks alright as well.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pq1bppp/1nn1p3/3pP3/p2P1P1P/PP1B1N2/4N1P1/1RBQK2R b Kkq - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...axb3  15.Rxb3  Nc4  16.O-O  g6  and  with the pawns on e6 and g6 firmly stopping White from playing f4-f5, Black finds good counterplay against White's queenside structure without exposing their king to danger. }
8... cxd4
{ A choice in more than half the games at both master-level and online games. By releasing the tension in the center, Black opens the diagonal for their bishop. I believe White holds an edge here, but we must be precise for the next few moves to keep Black's initiative in check @@StartBracket@@no puns intended@@EndBracket@@. }
9. cxd4 a5
{ After the pawn exchange on d4, advancing with ...a7-a5 now doesn't work as well with Black's queen on b6, which blocks the ...Nd7-b6-c4 maneuver. Plus, White doesn't have to rush playing Kf2 anymore since the c3 square is available for the knight.   If Black wanted to play ...a5, then play it immediately with @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P1P/2P2N2/PP4P1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq h3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a5  would have been better. }
10. Ne2 a4 11. Nc3
{ Playing  11.a3  makes the light squares weaker. Plus, we're more than ready to face Black's play on the queenside. }
11... a3 12. bxa3 Bxa3 13. Bxa3 Rxa3
{ Black has accomplished the goal of opening the queenside but at the cost of exchanging their stronger dark-squared bishop for White's weaker one. White can now shift the attention to queenside and harness the numerous weaknesses Black left, namely the open b- and c-files, as well as the d6-outpost. }
14. Nb5 Qa5+ 15. Kf2 Rxa2+ 16. Rxa2 Qxa2+ 17. Be2
{ Despite Black being ahead by a pawn, it is White who has persistent pressure on the board. Black's bishop is entombed and White controls the board. }
