{ A choice in more than half the games at both master-level and online games. By releasing the tension in the center, Black opens the diagonal for their bishop. I believe White holds an edge here, but we must be precise for the next few moves to keep Black's initiative in check @@StartBracket@@no puns intended@@EndBracket@@. }
9. cxd4 Be7 10. a3
{ Since Black has committed the queen to b6, slowing down the ...Nd7-b6-c4 maneuver, this is again a useful move to halt Black's queenside play. }
10... Na5
{ A clever attempt to exploit the weakened light squares on the queenside. }
11. Ne2
{ Playing  11.b4?  now would be a mistake, as it allows Black's knight to come to life with  11...Nc4  . }
11... Qb3
{ Against  11...Nb3  , the best solution is to let it happen and the bishop be traded!  We would rather welcome ...Nc6-a5-b3xc1 when the knight spends multiple moves just to exchange our undeveloped bishop that is stuck behind the pawn chain. For example, after  12.Rb1  Nxc1  13.Qxc1  O-O  14.Nc3  , White can continue  with Bd3 and Qe3, with good play. }
12. Qd2
{ We don't mind exchanging queens but let us delay it slightly and do it on our terms instead. }
12... Nc4 13. Qc3
{ Compared to a queen trade on the previous move, it turns out that Black's knight is a lot more unstable on c4 than it would be on b3. Soon, we will be able to remove it with b2-b3. }
13... Qxc3+ 14. Nxc3 Ndb6 15. b3 { Let's start pushing Black's knight back. }
15... Na5 16. Rb1
{ This positional concept of a3+b3 to shun out Black's knight is an instructive one. Without the support from Black's pawns, the knights are struggling to be effective on the queenside. White has the upper hand in this queenless middlegame. }
