Nxd4  Qc3+  , forking the bishop and rook. The author himself may have learned this nasty tactic the hard way...  11...Nb6  12.Bd3  cxd4  13.cxd4  a4  14.Ne2  . @@StartBracket@@After  14.b4  Bd7  ,  preparing ...Na7 and ...Bb5, Black's position looks alright as well.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pq1bppp/1nn1p3/3pP3/p2P1P1P/PP1B1N2/4N1P1/1RBQK2R b Kkq - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...axb3  15.Rxb3  Nc4  16.O-O  g6  and  with the pawns on e6 and g6 firmly stopping White from playing f4-f5, Black finds good counterplay against White's queenside structure without exposing their king to danger. }
8... cxd4
{ A choice in more than half the games at both master-level and online games. By releasing the tension in the center, Black opens the diagonal for their bishop. I believe White holds an edge here, but we must be precise for the next few moves to keep Black's initiative in check @@StartBracket@@no puns intended@@EndBracket@@. }
9. cxd4 Bb4+ 10. Kf2
{ Playing  10.Bd2  would end up losing  the d4-pawn after  10...Nxd4  . } 10...
Be7 11. Rb1
{ Our idea is to free the c1-bishop from the duty of defending the b2-pawn and allow Be3 to break the pin of the queen. }
11... f6 12. Be3 Qa5 13. a3 O-O 14. Kg3
{ 14.Nh3  was originally the move I'd suggest. But here, with the queen  on a5 @@StartBracket@@instead of b6@@EndBracket@@, Black does the option of going  14...fxe5  15.fxe5  Ndxe5  16.dxe5  Nxe5  , when after  17.Kg1  Ng4  18.Bd4  Bd6  ,  Black is ready to play ...e5. White should still be fine, but that requires a degree of precision. The move we chose instead is simpler, and rather fun, so why not? }
14... b5 15. Bd3 Bb7
{ 15...b4  runs into  16.Qc2  , targeting  both h7 and c6 at the same time. }
16. Ng5
{ White is set to have a great time. For instance,  16...fxg5  17.hxg5  Rf5  18.Rxh7  Kxh7  19.Bxf5+  exf5  20.Qh5+  Kg8  21.e6  Nf8  22.Qf7+  Kh8  23.Nf3  and  Black is rather helpless in stopping Rh1#. }
