{ This very rare move is absolutely critical for White. The knight is heading for the g5-square, and in conjunction with Bf1-d3 prepares a powerful attack on Black's king.   Previously, multiple masters games proceeded with  13.Bd3?!  Nxd4!  14.Ne2  Bc5  . With the center collapsing and White's king caught in the chaos, Black has a promising position.   It's also worth noting the instinctive  13.Kg3  , stepping out of the pin on the f-file, runs into  13...Ndxe5  , when Black wins a pawn thanks to the  undefended e3-bishop. }
13... Be7 { Attacking both the b2 and h4-pawns; which one should White save? }
14. Rb1
{ Protecting the b2-pawn is much more of a priority over the h4-pawn since we want to limit Black's counterplay on the queenside, even if such threats seem so far off right now. }
14... Bxh4+ 15. Kg1
{ All of a sudden, White's king finds itself safe on g1. The captured pawn on h4 may be a blessing in disguise, as White's rook on h1 will soon be a menace on the h-file. }
15... Be7 16. Bd3 h6
{ Exploiting the pin on the a7-g1 diagonal and undefended bishop on e3 with  16...Ndxe5  is met with a cold shower after  17.Bxh7+!  The continuation  17...Kxh7  18.Nfg5+  Kg6  19.Nf4+  Rxf4  20.Qh5+  Kf5  21.Rh4  Rxh4  22.Rf1+  is a rather brutal end. }
17. Qe2
{ The move 16...h6 makes the tactical ...Ndxe5 possible again, as Bxh7+ is no longer available. By protecting the bishop on e3, we stop Black from executing that idea once and for all.  The next few moves for White will likely be Rf1, Bb1, and Qd3, threatening Qh7+. Meanwhile, I encourage readers to come up with a single plausible plan for Black. The engine is already shouting +3 despite Black being the one pawn up! }
