[Black "Open System 3...c5 4.exd5 cxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... cxd4 { Taking the wrong pawn could put Black in a tough spot. } 5. Bb5+
{ This unpleasant check disrupts Black's plan. We aim to take on e6 and prevent Black's bishop from capturing back. }
5... Bd7 6. dxe6 fxe6
{ After  6...Bxb5  , Black could face trouble with  7.exf7  Kxf7  8.Qh5+  , when White simply regains material with a fork on the king and bishop. }
7. Bd3
{ The removal of Black's f-pawn and the extended d-pawn has presented White with two powerful outpost squares on e4 and e5. }
7... Nf6 8. Ngf3 Nc6 9. O-O Qc7 10. Re1
{ Black's overextended central pawns are nothing but weaknesses. We can now look to occupy the central outpost on e4 and e5, before mounting pressure on the e6-pawn. }
