[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Open System 3...c5 4.exd5 exd5"]
[Black "Open System 4...exd5 5.Ngf3 a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... exd5
{ This move is arguably one of Black's most reliable options in the French Tarrasch. Our best chance for an advantage will be to eventually capture the pawn on c5, leading to a position where Black has just a single d5-pawn in the center and no e- or c-pawns @@StartBracket@@known as an isolated queen's pawn or IQP for short@@EndBracket@@.  We'll delve into IQPs more thoroughly later, but it is noteworthy that an IQP is a double-edged sword. It's important to keep that pawn under control and limit Black's piece activity. }
5. Ngf3 a6
{ A direct approach to stopping Bb5+; this move is actually the third most common choice at the master level, behind  5...Nf6  and  5...Nc6  . }
6. Qe2+
{ Though rare, this move can create significant problems for Black, as it forces an awkward decision on how to block the check. The standard line of  6.Be2  c4  7.O-O  Bd6  8.b3  also leaves White with a slight edge. }
6... Be7
{ Black temporarily sacrifices the c5-pawn in exchange for quick development.   6...Be6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Nb3  Ba7  9.Be3  leaves White with a comfortable IQP position, thanks to the full control of  the d4-outpost. }
7. dxc5 Nf6 8. Nb3 O-O
{ It may appear that Black is building some dangerous initiative, especially with the queen on e2 feeling awkward against the threat of ...Re8. }
9. Qd1
{ We calmly retreat our queen to d1, clearing the e2-square for our light-squared bishop and preparing to castle kingside into safety. While this may seem like a loss of tempo, we've reached a pleasant IQP position where White maintains excellent control of the d4-square and remains a pawn up for now.   It is worth noting that castling queenside is also an option with  9.Be3  Re8  10.O-O-O!?  , though this allows Black some play beginning with  10...a5! }
9... Nbd7
{ Black can also immediately regain the pawn with  9...Bxc5  . After  10.Nxc5  Qa5+  11.c3  Qxc5  12.Be3  Qc7  13.Be2  Nc6  14.O-O  , White has dominant control over the dark squares, the bishop pair, and the  key d4-outpost. }
10. Be3 Re8 11. Be2 Qc7 12. O-O
{ It's also worth considering  12.Qd4!?  , aiming  to hold onto the c5-pawn for as long as possible. }
12... Nxc5 13. Nxc5 Bxc5 14. Bxc5 Qxc5 15. c3
{ Black finally recaptures the c5-pawn, but at what cost? In IQP positions, the more pieces White trades, the more vulnerable Black's d5-pawn becomes. White holds a slight edge here, with excellent control over the d4-outpost and a superior bishop. Black's pawns, especially the d5-pawn, are mostly on light squares, making them easy targets for White's bishop in the long run. }
