1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... exd5
{ This move is arguably one of Black's most reliable options in the French Tarrasch. Our best chance for an advantage will be to eventually capture the pawn on c5, leading to a position where Black has just a single d5-pawn in the center and no e- or c-pawns @@StartBracket@@known as an isolated queen's pawn or IQP for short@@EndBracket@@.  We'll delve into IQPs more thoroughly later, but it is noteworthy that an IQP is a double-edged sword. It's important to keep that pawn under control and limit Black's piece activity. }
5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Qe7+
{ This is rarely played but in my opinion a rather annoying move to face. } 7.
Qe2
{ White shouldn't oppose a queen trade, as most endings are rather pleasant. }
7... Qxe2+ 8. Kxe2 a6
{ This is one of the main points of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qe7+  . White indeed has the better pawn structure after the  capture on c6, but Black will gain the bishop pair with active play in return. }
9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Re1
{ Placing the rook on the open file is a natural reaction.   The alternative  10.Ne5  was my choice against Ryder Testolin in the 2023 Oceania Zonal. In the game, I was hit with the rather convincing  10...c4  , when I decided against capturing the pawn with  11.Nxc6  in fear of the knight being trapped after  11...f6  . Even though I managed to win that game, it had little to do with the opening. }
10... f6 { Black vacates the f7-square for the king. } 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Nb3
Bd6 13. Be3
{ We will look to occupy the dark squares in the center with Bc5 and trade off its counterpart, removing Black's bishop pair from the equation. }
13... Ne7 14. Bc5 Bxc5
{ Capturing on c5 allows White to dominate the central dark squares without facing serious resistance. }
15. Nxc5 Kf7 16. Nd4
{ Just compare those minor pieces! Black's bishop and knight are overpowered by White's centralized knights. }
16... a5 17. Kd2 Ra7 18. a4
{ White has achieved a dream endgame position. The knights on c5 and d4 tie Black's pieces down, while a5 is a permanent weakness. We will slowly ramp up the pressure with Re2 and Rae1, as well as a potential c3 and b4 on the horizon to create a passed a-pawn. }
