{ This move is arguably one of Black's most reliable options in the French Tarrasch. Our best chance for an advantage will be to eventually capture the pawn on c5, leading to a position where Black has just a single d5-pawn in the center and no e- or c-pawns @@StartBracket@@known as an isolated queen's pawn or IQP for short@@EndBracket@@.  We'll delve into IQPs more thoroughly later, but it is noteworthy that an IQP is a double-edged sword. It's important to keep that pawn under control and limit Black's piece activity. }
5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Nf6
{ According to the online lichess database, this move has been played more than any other moves in this position, even though the move itself is a mistake!   The shortcoming of  6...Nf6  is that unlike  6...Bd6  followed by ...Nge7, it does little to defend the open e-file. }
7. O-O
{ As it turns out, Black doesn't have the luxury of time on their side. With the move Re1+ incoming, Black will likely have to concede a pawn or risk the king being stranded in the center. }
