9... Be6 { The most natural way of blocking the check. } 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nbd4
O-O
{ Black finally castles and chooses to sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. Here we have to be careful with how we plan to win material. }
12. Bxc6
{ 12.Nxe6  fxe6  13.Rxe6  would allow Black too much counterplay. After  13...Bxf2+!  14.Kxf2  Qb6+  , Black forks the king and bishop, regaining the material balance but with a dangerous initiative thanks to the open f-file. }
12... bxc6 13. Nxc6
{ Once again, it is key to restrict Black's counterplay. Capturing the wrong piece with  13.Nxe6  would leave White under a dangerous attack after  13...fxe6  14.Rxe6  Ng4! }
13... Qd6 14. Ncd4 Bg4 15. Be3 Rfe8 16. Qd3
{ Despite Black having the bishop pair, White is a clear pawn up with a solid position. The next step will be to consolidate the position with c3 and h3, before focusing on the d5-pawn with Rad1 and Nf5. }
