{ We take control of the e-file and prepare to exchange a pair of bishops with Be3. }
10... O-O 11. Be3 Bc7
{ On the strategic level, it makes good sense for Black to avoid trading more pieces.   The immediate  11...Bg4  is met with  12.h3!  , when after the natural  11...Bh5  , White gets to trade a pair of bishops with  12.Bxb6  axb6  13.Qd3  . White breaks the pin and is ready to occupy  the d4-outpost with Nbd4 and c2-c3.  Instead, @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2nppp/1Bn5/1B1p3b/8/1N3N1P/PPP2PP1/R2QR1K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  12...Qxb6?  loses a pawn after  13.Bxc6  Nxc6  14.Qxd5  . }
12. Bc5 Re8 13. Qd2 { Sidestepping the pin from ...Bg4. } 13... a6 14. Bxe7
{ Again we will exchange into a favorable endgame. } 14... Rxe7 15. Bxc6 bxc6
16. Rxe7 Qxe7 17. Re1 Qd8 18. Qc3
{ After the smoke has settled, we have successfully taken over the queenside dark squares with a nice positional edge. After  18...Bd7  19.Ne5  Rc8  20.Nc5  , it is clear that the knights completely dominate the position. Black's bishops are unable to realize their true potential owing to the  weaknesses on a6 and c6. }
