{ We reached the main IQP position of the French Tarrasch. An isolated queen's pawn is a rather common occurrence in numerous openings and has rather double-edged characteristics. On one hand, it controls more space and allows pieces to develop actively. On the other hand, the isolated pawn can become a weakness in the long term. In particular, the square in front of it @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@ can serve as a powerful outpost.  Based on these observations, we can conclude that this IQP position slightly favors White. The slight concession of the knight going to e7, coupled with the fact that White is very much ready to control the d4-outpost, both suggest that White has a pleasant time ahead. The IQP is more of a liability than an asset in this regard. }
9... Bd6
{ This is by far Black's most popular reply from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/3P4/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...exd5  .  Black manages to keep most pieces on the board, which compensates the d5-IQP with potential complications. The slight downside is the placement of Black's knight to e7 instead of the natural f6. }
10. c3 { Pushing the pawn to c3 allow us to consolidate the d4-outpost. } 10...
O-O 11. Bd3
{ Now that Black has castled and the pin on b5 is no longer in existence, we can relocate our bishop to a much more active diagonal − not to mention we are stopping ...Bg4 tactically. }
11... Bf5
{ This is commonly played. But trading the bishops rather makes White's life easier. }
12. Bxf5 Nxf5 13. g3
{ 13.Qxd5  runs into  13...Bxh2+  , when the discovered attack wins the queen.  By playing g2-g3 and avoiding the discovered attack, we now renew the attack on the d5-pawn. }
13... Nfe7 14. Re1 Qd7 15. Be3 { Aiming to trade the bishops with Be3-c5. }
15... b6 { Black prevents further trade of minor pieces. } 16. Rc1
{ Our rook on a1 isn't in the game, so it makes sense to prepare the doubling of the rooks with Rc1-c2-e2. }
16... Rad8 17. Rc2 f6 18. Rce2 Ne5 19. Nfd4
{ 19.Nxe5  fxe5  would rather turn Black's  weak d5-pawn into a part of a strong center. We shall not allow that. The knight on e5 is now rather vulnerable to f2-f4. }
19... N7c6 20. Kg2
{ With Kg2, we make sure to avoid any nasty business with ...Qh3 and ...Ng4/f3+. Our plan next involves exchanging on c6 to bring our other knight to d4 and a potential f2-f4 to follow. Black will have to bear the long-term burden of IQP, while White is in a prime position thanks to the doubled rooks on the open e-file. }
