10. c3 { Pushing the pawn to c3 allow us to consolidate the d4-outpost. } 10...
O-O 11. Bd3
{ Now that Black has castled and the pin on b5 is no longer in existence, we can relocate our bishop to a much more active diagonal − not to mention we are stopping ...Bg4 tactically. }
11... h6 12. h3 { Primarily played to prevent ...Bg4. } 12... Bf5 13. Re1
{ Since we had already committed h2-h3, our previous approach to @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2nb4/3p4/8/1NPB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bf5  with g2-g3 makes less sense. Instead, we can put pressure on Black's isolated pawn in a different way. }
13... Qd7 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 15. Kf1
{ Similarly to the idea of g2-g3; by sidestepping the check on h2, we put pressure on the d5-pawn. }
15... Be7 16. Qd3 Rad8 17. Bf4 Bf6 18. Rad1
{ Despite Black's best efforts, they were unable to get rid of the weak pawn on d5. Instead, we have our pieces on optimal squares and can slowly strengthen our position with Qd3-b5 and Nb3-c5. }
