[White "4) Open System 3...c5 4.exd5 Qxd5"]
[Black "Open System 4...Qxd5 5.Ngf3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... Qxd5
{ In my opinion, this is the most critical test for White in the French Tarrasch. While developing the queen early tends to be a disadvantage, here it is somewhat justified because White's knight on d2 prevents Nb1-c3, which would typically harass the queen for tempo.  The knight also blocks White's queen on d1, leaving the d4-pawn vulnerable. On the flip side, we can speedily develop our pieces, and the queen will inevitably be chased around. }
5. Ngf3 Nf6
{ Not capturing the pawn on d4 is playable, but it does allow White to develop rapidly without any trouble. }
6. Bc4 { White gains a tempo attacking the queen. } 6... Qd8 7. Nb3 cxd4 8.
Nbxd4
{ White solidifies the control over the center. Compared to the main line we will soon explore, the extra pair of knights on the board @@StartBracket@@f3 and b8@@EndBracket@@ benefits White. We plan to quickly castle queenside and initiate a pawn storm against Black's king on the kingside. }
8... Be7 9. Qe2
{ Instead of the routine kingside castling with  9.O-O  , we will opt for a more aggressive approach with queenside castling. Generally in the French Defense, if Black does not disturb our development, it makes more sense for us to castle queenside, especially if Black castles kingside which they often do. Our attack usually accelerates with the pawn  thrust g2-g4. }
9... O-O 10. Bg5 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qc7 12. O-O-O
{ Now that White has completed development, it is time to shift attention to the kingside attack. We want to exploit the slower development of Black's queenside pieces. }
12... a6 13. Rhe1 b5 14. Bd3 Rd8 15. g4
{ White has a dangerous attack ready to go. } *

