10. O-O-O Bd7
{ Already this is the only move that prevents Black from collapsing under pressure. Instead,  10...Be7  runs into  11.Nd6+  Bxd6  12.Bxd6  Bd7  13.Ne5  , when White has complete control and Black is in serious trouble.   Eliminating the knight doesn't solve Black's development issues. After  10...Nxe4  11.Qxe4  Qc5  12.Bb3  Bd7  , White should refrain from  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.Rxd4  Bc6  ,  when Black is in time to bring the king to safety following ...Be7 and ...O-O.  Instead, @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1b1ppp/2n1p3/2q5/3pQB2/1B3N2/PPP2PPP/2KR3R w kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Be5  O-O-O  14.Bxd4  Nxd4  15.Rxd4  keeps the momentum, as Black still has to work hard to find equality. }
11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. Bxd6 O-O-O 13. Rd3
{ Despite the extra pawn, Black is finding it increasingly difficult to find a proactive plan. Meanwhile, White can continue with moves like Rb3 and Rhd1 for active and threatening play. }
