1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... Qxd5
{ In my opinion, this is the most critical test for White in the French Tarrasch. While developing the queen early tends to be a disadvantage, here it is somewhat justified because White's knight on d2 prevents Nb1-c3, which would typically harass the queen for tempo.  The knight also blocks White's queen on d1, leaving the d4-pawn vulnerable. On the flip side, we can speedily develop our pieces, and the queen will inevitably be chased around. }
5. Ngf3 cxd4
{ The most natural response. Black won't be able to keep the extra pawn, but at least they can develop rapidly in the time it takes White to recover the pawn. }
6. Bc4 { Attacking the queen and allowing us to develop rapidly. } 6... Qd8
{ Usually, the queen retreats to d7 and d8 will transpose to  6...Qd6  . For example,  6...Qd7  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Nb3  Nf6  9.Nbxd4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qc7  and we reached our main line.   However, the advantage of  going to d8 @@StartBracket@@or d7@@EndBracket@@ is that it does not obstruct the development of the f8-bishop, enabling an additional possibility of ...Bc5. }
7. O-O Nc6 { 7...Nf6  8.Nb3  Nc6  transposes to the text. } 8. Nb3 Nf6
{ 8...a6  is another reasonable move and would likely lead us to the lines similar to 6...Qd6. For instance, after  9.Nbxd4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qc7  , we have reached our main line with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3q4/2Bp4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qd6  . }
9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc5
{ Putting immediate pressure on our knight. We no longer have the option of going b2-b3 and Bb2 as in the rest of the chapter. }
11. Nb3
{ As it turns out, we aren't exactly afraid of a queen trade. In fact, the pawn structure of 3 vs. 2 on the queenside actually favors us. The logic is that when both kings are on the kingside, White's extra pawn, which has the potential to turn into a passed pawn, is much more dangerous further away from the king. }
11... Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bb6 13. a4
{ We are threatening to expand on the queenside, potentially fixing Black’s a- and b-pawns as long-term targets. }
13... O-O { Allows the realization of our plan. } 14. a5
{ We force the retreat of Black's bishop and prepare to pressure Black's queenside pawns with Nc5 and Be3-c5. }
14... Bc7 15. Be3 Ng4 16. Bc5
{ We are happy to leave our h2-pawn temporarily undefended since after  16...Bxh2+  17.Kh1  , Black cannot stop the threats  of Bxf8 and f3, chasing away Black's knight that is defending the h2-bishop. If Black instead moves the rook, we will kick the knight back with h3 and enjoy a pleasant initiative on the queenside. }
