{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... Qxd5
{ In my opinion, this is the most critical test for White in the French Tarrasch. While developing the queen early tends to be a disadvantage, here it is somewhat justified because White's knight on d2 prevents Nb1-c3, which would typically harass the queen for tempo.  The knight also blocks White's queen on d1, leaving the d4-pawn vulnerable. On the flip side, we can speedily develop our pieces, and the queen will inevitably be chased around. }
5. Ngf3 cxd4
{ The most natural response. Black won't be able to keep the extra pawn, but at least they can develop rapidly in the time it takes White to recover the pawn. }
6. Bc4 { Attacking the queen and allowing us to develop rapidly. } 6... Qd7
{ This is a tricky move order. As we will see shortly, by placing the queen on d7, Black effectively neutralizes the sting of our b3 setup. }
7. O-O Nc6 8. Nb3 Nf6 9. Qe2
{ Instead of regaining the pawn with  9.Nbxd4  , which works well in lines  involving ...Qd6, here it’s more complicated because the queen on d7 is well-positioned against our typical plan of b3 and Bb2. For example, after  9...Nxd4  10.Nxd4  a6  11.b3?!  b5  ,  unlike with ...Qd6, we no longer have  12.Qf3?  as an option since it loses a piece to  12...Bb7  with the queen on d7 protecting the bishop.   However, with  9.Qe2!?  , we turn the tables by exploiting the fact that the queen  on d7, unlike on d6, doesn't protect the e5-square. This gives us time to regain the pawn through a different plan, starting with Rd1 before capturing on d4. This approach wouldn't have worked against  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3q4/2Bp4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qd6  , as Black would control  the e5-square and be able to play  7.O-O  Nf6  8.Nb3  Nc6  9.Qe2  Be7  10.Rd1  e5  . }
9... Bd6
{ If Black focuses on development instead of disrupting White's natural plan of Rd1 and Nbxd4, the rook on the d-file can quickly become a serious problem for Black. }
10. Rd1
{ Already, we are ready to regain the d4-pawn with our well-centralized pieces. }
10... O-O 11. Nbxd4 Nxd4 12. Rxd4
{ The rook is incredibly strong on d4 and can swing over to h4 for a devastating attack on the king. }
12... Qc7 13. Rh4
{ With Bd3 and Bg5 on the way, the attack flows naturally and almost plays itself. For instance, after  13...a6?!  14.Bg5  Be7  15.Bd3  h6  16.Bxh6  gxh6  17.Qe3  , Black is completely defenseless against White's crushing attack. }
