{ Before shifting the rook to h4 for a kingside attack, we first provoke Black's queen onto the d5-square, where it will face some trouble once our a1-rook develops to d1. }
17... Qd5 18. Rh4
{ We enjoy a strong attack against Black's king and can proceed with either Bg5 or b3 and Bb2.   For example, after  18...h6?  , White delivers a spectacular blow with  19.Bxh6  gxh6  20.Qe3  , and Black has no way to prevent the queen from  landing on h6, which spells doom for Black's king. }
