[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... Qxd5
{ In my opinion, this is the most critical test for White in the French Tarrasch. While developing the queen early tends to be a disadvantage, here it is somewhat justified because White's knight on d2 prevents Nb1-c3, which would typically harass the queen for tempo.  The knight also blocks White's queen on d1, leaving the d4-pawn vulnerable. On the flip side, we can speedily develop our pieces, and the queen will inevitably be chased around. }
5. Ngf3 cxd4
{ The most natural response. Black won't be able to keep the extra pawn, but at least they can develop rapidly in the time it takes White to recover the pawn. }
6. Bc4 { Attacking the queen and allowing us to develop rapidly. } 6... Qd6
{ The most popular retreat. However, there is also a chance that  6...Qd8  likely transpose to the main line. For example,  6...Qd8  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Nb3  Nf6  9.Nbxd4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qc7  and we reached our main line. }
7. O-O
{ First, we get our king to safety and avoid any funny businesses involving ...Qb4+.   For instance,  7.Nb3  Qb4+  , when White's best option is to bring the knight  back to d2 with  8.Nbd2  . }
7... Nc6
{ A slight inaccuracy in the move order, which gives White the extra option of going Ne4! }
8. Ne4
{ Without the knight on f6, we can take advantage of the active e4-square. }
8... Qd8 9. Qe2 { We will regain the d4-pawn with the natural Rd1 and c3. }
9... Nf6 { 9...Be7  10.Rd1  Nf6  transposes. } 10. Rd1 Be7 11. c3 O-O 12. Nxd4
{ We regain the d-pawn and thanks to our rook on d1 hold control of the open d-file. }
12... Nxd4 13. Rxd4 Qc7 14. Bd3
{ Our rook on d4 can be swung in both directions for active operations. Let us also spare a thought for Black.   Hoping to develop the light-squared bishop with  14...b6  is effectively countered with  15.Nxf6  Bxf6  16.Bf4!  e5  17.Qe4  , threatening mate  on h7 as well as capturing the rook on a8. }
