{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... Qxd5
{ In my opinion, this is the most critical test for White in the French Tarrasch. While developing the queen early tends to be a disadvantage, here it is somewhat justified because White's knight on d2 prevents Nb1-c3, which would typically harass the queen for tempo.  The knight also blocks White's queen on d1, leaving the d4-pawn vulnerable. On the flip side, we can speedily develop our pieces, and the queen will inevitably be chased around. }
5. Ngf3 cxd4
{ The most natural response. Black won't be able to keep the extra pawn, but at least they can develop rapidly in the time it takes White to recover the pawn. }
6. Bc4 { Attacking the queen and allowing us to develop rapidly. } 6... Qd6
{ The most popular retreat. However, there is also a chance that  6...Qd8  likely transpose to the main line. For example,  6...Qd8  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Nb3  Nf6  9.Nbxd4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qc7  and we reached our main line. }
7. O-O
{ First, we get our king to safety and avoid any funny businesses involving ...Qb4+.   For instance,  7.Nb3  Qb4+  , when White's best option is to bring the knight  back to d2 with  8.Nbd2  . }
7... Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4
{ This is the main tabiya of the chapter, with more than 2700 master games played to date from the 4500 games after 4...Qxd5. }
10... Qc7
{ A logical retreat. Black often vacates the d6-square for the dark-squared bishop to set up a battery on the h2-pawn and threaten our king. Omitting ...a7-a6 is usually a poor decision from Black. White always has an untimely Nb5. }
11. b3
{ This key move is the main part of our repertoire against 4...Qxd5.   Instead of the conventional  11.Re1  followed by Bg5, we will fianchetto our bishop to b2. The bishop on b2 will assist in controlling the e5-square with Nf3-e5, as well as a potential attack on the kingside with Bxf6. }
11... Bd6 12. Nb5 { White can sacrifice the h2-pawn to expose Black's queen. }
12... Bxh2+ 13. Kh1 Qb8 14. g3 { The bishop is trapped. } 14... Bxg3 15. fxg3
Qxg3
{ At first, Black appears to have adequate compensation for the bishop with three pawns and the possibility of a perpetual with ...Qh3+ and ...Qg3. However, it is actually Black's king who is in greater danger. }
16. Nd6+ Kf8
{ 16...Ke7  17.Nf5+  is also doomed.  17...exf5  18.Ba3+  and  Black cannot deal with the threat of Re1+ and Bb5+. }
17. Nf5
{ Let's fuel the attack further by opening the a3-f8 diagonal for the bishop on c1! }
17... Qh3+ 18. Kg1
{ The combined threat of Qd8+ and Ba3+ is simply too strong for Black to handle. }
