[White "4) Open System 3...c5 4.exd5 Qxd5"]
[Black "Open System 4...Qxd5 − 6...Qd6 7.O-O Nf6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is a critical attempt from Black. The key behind ...c5 is to undermine the one downside to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  , which unlike  3.Nc3  does not put pressure on Black's central pawns immediately. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Ngf3  is a promising alternative. However, by exchanging  on d5 right away, we reduce the number of lines we need to know dramatically. Here Black has two means to recapture, both of which are equally viable. }
4... Qxd5
{ In my opinion, this is the most critical test for White in the French Tarrasch. While developing the queen early tends to be a disadvantage, here it is somewhat justified because White's knight on d2 prevents Nb1-c3, which would typically harass the queen for tempo.  The knight also blocks White's queen on d1, leaving the d4-pawn vulnerable. On the flip side, we can speedily develop our pieces, and the queen will inevitably be chased around. }
5. Ngf3 cxd4
{ The most natural response. Black won't be able to keep the extra pawn, but at least they can develop rapidly in the time it takes White to recover the pawn. }
6. Bc4 { Attacking the queen and allowing us to develop rapidly. } 6... Qd6
{ The most popular retreat. However, there is also a chance that  6...Qd8  likely transpose to the main line. For example,  6...Qd8  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Nb3  Nf6  9.Nbxd4  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qc7  and we reached our main line. }
7. O-O
{ First, we get our king to safety and avoid any funny businesses involving ...Qb4+.   For instance,  7.Nb3  Qb4+  , when White's best option is to bring the knight  back to d2 with  8.Nbd2  . }
7... Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4
{ This is the main tabiya of the chapter, with more than 2700 master games played to date from the 4500 games after 4...Qxd5. }
10... Be7
{ This is a rather timid but solid move. Black simply wants to castle before deciding the next step. }
11. b3 { Once again our bishop belongs on the long diagonal. } 11... O-O 12.
Bb2 Qf4
{ This move is recommended by Anish Giri in his French LTR, so it certainly deserves consideration. Now that our bishop is on the a1-h8 diagonal, the queen is well-placed on f4, where it disrupts our plan of a kingside attack with Bd3 and Qf3-h3. Black is ready to follow up with ...Rd8, ...b6, and ...Bb7 with a solid position. }
13. a4
{ With  13.a4!?  , we anticipate Black's idea of  playing ...b6 in advance.   Instead, trading queens with  13.Qf3  Qxf3  14.Nxf3  b6  15.a4  Bb7  16.a5  Be4  allows Black to find comfortable play in this queenless middlegame. }
13... Rd8
{ Black can try to use the d-file pin against our queen on d1; it's not as dangerous as it first appears. }
14. Bd3
{ Blocking the d-file allows us to improve our position with Nf3 and Be5.   The knight on d4 is untouchable, as  14...Rxd4?  runs into  15.Bxd4  Qxd4  16.Bxh7+  , a discovered attack that wins the queen. }
14... a6
{ Alternatively, after  14...b6  , White can strike with  15.Nc6!  , winning the bishop pair with an excellent position. Following  15...Rd7  16.Nxe7+  Rxe7  17.g3  Qh6  18.h4  , White can play actively on both sides of the board with ideas  like a5 and Bc1. }
15. Nf3
{ Vacating the diagonal to enable the e5-square for our dark-squared bishop, while also preparing to chase away the troublesome queen on f4. }
15... b6 16. Be5 Qb4
{ Now we can see that Black's queen is forced to retreat, giving us multiple tempi to firmly establish control over the position. }
17. c3 Qc5 18. b4 Qd5 19. Bd4
{ White has a nice position with the bishops dominating the entire board. We can follow up with Qe2-e3 and Rfd1, amplifying the pressure on Black's queenside and the weak pawn on b6. }
