{ This is the main part of our repertoire against 4...Qxd5.   Instead of the conventional  11.Re1  followed by Bg5, we opt to fianchetto the bishop on b2. This bishop will play a crucial role in controlling the e5-square with potentially Nf3-e5 and can also assist in a kingside attack by targeting the f6-knight with Bxf6. }
11... Qc7
{ A logical retreat. Black vacates the d6-square for the dark-squared bishop to set up a battery and threaten our king. }
12. Bb2 Bd6 { The queen & bishop battery starts pressuring our h2-pawn. } 13.
Nf3
{ Retreating the knight back to f3 not only defends the h2-pawn but also prepares to dominate the e5-square with Re1 followed by Ne5. }
13... O-O { Surprisingly, this move turns out to be slightly inaccurate. } 14.
Qd4
{ The queen is coming to h4, where it is ready to create serious threats to Black's king. }
14... b5 15. Bd3 Bb7 16. Qh4
{ Threatening to remove the knight with Bxf6 followed by checkmate on h7. }
16... e5
{ Black is forced into the only move that prevents immediate disaster. } 17. c4
{ It always makes sense to include c4 when we can since we pressure Black's queenside and the natural ...b4 would hand White a valuable passed pawn. The other choices are no better, as they simply open another avenue for White to control the c-file with Rac1. }
17... b4
{ Instead, capturing the pawn with  17...bxc4  runs into  18.Rac1  , preparing  to recapture on c4 with the rook. The follow-up with Rc4-g4 will put us in a dominant position to unleash an attack on Black's king.   17...e4  runs into  18.Bxf6  , when shutting down the diagonal for  the d3-bishop actually opens the a1-h8 diagonal for the other bishop.   Finally,  17...Bxf3  18.gxf3  doesn't quite weaken our king but rather offers an extra attacking option.  By playing Kh1 and subsequently Rg1, we turn what could be a vulnerability into a fierce attack. The open g-file allows our rook to join the attack. }
18. Rae1 Rfe8 19. Bb1
{ White's pieces are optimally placed on active squares, and we can continue to amplify the kingside attack by bringing our rook into play with Re3, Ne1, and Rg3. }
