{ The most natural move here, as Black threatens ...e4, aiming to fork White's bishop and knight.   Instead, capturing the pawn with  17...bxc4  runs into  18.Rac1  , preparing  to recapture on c4 with the rook. The follow-up with Rc4-g4 will put us in a dominant position to unleash an attack on Black's king.   17...e4  runs into  18.Bxf6  , when shutting down the diagonal for  the d3-bishop actually opens the a1-h8 diagonal for the other bishop.   Finally,  17...Bxf3  18.gxf3  doesn't quite weaken our king but rather offers an extra attacking option.  By playing Kh1 and subsequently Rg1, we turn what could be a vulnerability into a fierce attack. The open g-file allows our rook to join the attack. }
