Nf3
{ Retreating the knight back to f3 not only defends the h2-pawn but also prepares to dominate the e5-square with Re1 followed by Ne5. }
13... b5
{ Pushing the bishop back now is crucial to deprive White the chance to shift the queen to h4. }
14. Bd3 Bb7 15. c4
{ Once again, we will include this move to target Black's extended queenside pawns. }
15... Ng4
{ Black can also choose to go for a direct attack on our king.   Winning the pawn on h2 with  15...Bxf3  16.Qxf3  Bxh2+  is too dangerous for Black. After  17.Kh1  ,  Black cannot defend against the dual threats of Qxa8+ and g3, trapping the h2-bishop. Instead, Black sacrifices the queenside pawn in Benko Gambit style, relying on rapid development and the threats around White's king. }
16. cxb5
{ This move leads to a forced draw, but only if Black manages to find the next couple of critical moves. I will leave it to you to judge whether your opponent is up to such a challenge.   If you are looking to keep the game going, then maybe it is also worth considering  16.h3  , when Black needs to find the brilliant  16...Bh2+  17.Kh1  Bg1!  18.Be5!  Nxe5  19.Nxe5  Qxe5  20.Kxg1  to emerge with a roughly equal position. }
16... Bxh2+ 17. Kh1 Qc5
{ The only move to equality; the queen is joining the attack via h5. } 18. bxa6
{ 18.Nxh2  runs into the nasty  18...Nxf2+  19.Rxf2  Qxf2  , when Black threatens the  checkmate on g2 as well as the hanging bishop on b2. }
18... Qh5
{ Black has no better than a perpetual check here. The attack ends abruptly after  18...Bc6  19.Qc1!  Qd5  20.Be2  , when White stops  the threat of ...Qxf3 followed by ...Bxf3# and prepares to exchange queens with Qg5. }
19. axb7 Bg3+ 20. Kg1 Bh2+ 21. Kh1
{ Neither side has anything better than to repeat moves and accept the draw by repetition. }
