[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Rubinstein 3...dxe4"]
[Black "Fort Knox 3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 Bd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ The Rubinstein Variation. By capturing on e4 early, Black concedes the center and grants White a space advantage, which Black hopes to neutralize with their solid setup. }
4. Nxe4
{ Compared to its Caro-Kann cousin, capturing on e4 early is less common, as ...e6 hampers the development of Black's light-squared bishop.   In the Caro-Kann, a line like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  dxe4  4.Nxe4  allows the bishop to develop with  4...Bf5  and  4...Nf6  .   Instead, here Black faces an interesting choice. Black must decide whether to realign the bishop along the a8-h1 diagonal directly, for example with ...Bd7-c6, or delay the bishop's development in favor of other pieces and only then develop it with ...b6 followed by ...Bb7.  Now that we recognize Black's main ideas, we should reflect on White's pluses. White's space advantage is undisputed, and our bishops are much more active than their counterparts. Furthermore, we retain the possibility of castling either side. }
4... Bd7
{ The Fort Knox, first played by none other than Capablanca in 1902 − the defense has a rather solid reputation. In essence, Black plans to play ...Bc6 before completing development with ...Nd7 and ...Ngf6. Eventually, the bishop will be traded for one of White's knights and the position will resemble a typical Caro-Kann where Black's position is solid, albeit passive. }
5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Bxe4
{ A common theme in the Fort Knox is the trade of Black's light-squared bishop for White's knight. The bishop on c6 obstructs the c-pawn, and a main source of Black's counterplay comes from ...c7-c5. Here, however, the capture is rather premature. Not only does it hand White the bishop pair, but Black is not yet ready to go for ...c5. }
7. Bxe4 c6 8. c3 Nf6 9. Bc2
{ White can now calmly complete development with Qe2, Bd2, and O-O-O, and enjoy a pleasant position. One note worth pointing out is that placing the bishop on a more active square on f4 often gets chased away by ...Nd5, while on g5 it invites ...h6. On d2, the bishop is safer and we retain the option of activating the bishop later. }
*

