{ The Fort Knox, first played by none other than Capablanca in 1902 − the defense has a rather solid reputation. In essence, Black plans to play ...Bc6 before completing development with ...Nd7 and ...Ngf6. Eventually, the bishop will be traded for one of White's knights and the position will resemble a typical Caro-Kann where Black's position is solid, albeit passive. }
5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. Qe2
{ Despite Black's solid setup, our pieces are much more active and thus we should be more ambitious with our approach.   Instead of settling for the safe but rather timid  7.O-O  , we want to mobilize our queenside pieces to prepare for queenside castling.  This will help set the stage for an explosive game with a kingside pawn storm involving g4 and h4. }
7... Ngf6 8. Bd2 Nxe4
{ Fort Knox is named for its cramped but robust defensive setup. Therefore, Black welcomes piece trades, which will give the remaining pieces some breathing room in a rather cramped position. }
9. Bxe4 Bxe4 10. Qxe4 c6
{ Completing the solid ...c6 and ... e6 setup and stopping Qxb7. } 11. O-O-O
{ Let's go for it! With opposite-side castling comes a possible pawn storm for both sides. Files and diagonals will be opened and our active pieces will prove to make a difference. }
11... Be7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. h4 { Initiating a pawn storm on Black's king. } 13...
Nf6 14. Kb1
{ White enjoys a pleasant initiative, notably our attack is much quicker thanks to our more active piece placement. }
