[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Rubinstein 3...dxe4"]
[Black "Rubinstein 3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ The Rubinstein Variation. By capturing on e4 early, Black concedes the center and grants White a space advantage, which Black hopes to neutralize with their solid setup. }
4. Nxe4
{ Compared to its Caro-Kann cousin, capturing on e4 early is less common, as ...e6 hampers the development of Black's light-squared bishop.   In the Caro-Kann, a line like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  dxe4  4.Nxe4  allows the bishop to develop with  4...Bf5  and  4...Nf6  .   Instead, here Black faces an interesting choice. Black must decide whether to realign the bishop along the a8-h1 diagonal directly, for example with ...Bd7-c6, or delay the bishop's development in favor of other pieces and only then develop it with ...b6 followed by ...Bb7.  Now that we recognize Black's main ideas, we should reflect on White's pluses. White's space advantage is undisputed, and our bishops are much more active than their counterparts. Furthermore, we retain the possibility of castling either side. }
4... Nf6
{ Black immediately challenges our centralized knight; usually, this is first prepared with ...Nd7 to allow Black to recapture with the knight. }
5. Nxf6+
{ Now Black faces an interesting dilemma: to capture the knight with the pawn or the queen? Each option comes with its distinct drawback. Capturing with the g-pawn leaves permanently weakened doubled f-pawns, whereas the other capture leaves the queen potentially in an awkward position on f6. }
5... gxf6
{ Black accepts the doubled f-pawns, which could pose as a long-term weakness. While technically Black's h8-rook stands to benefit from the open g-file, it is also much harder for Black's king to find safety with the kingside wide open. }
6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bc4 { Primarily to stop ...e5. } 7... b6
{ With  7...e5  8.Be3  Bg4  9.d5  Ne7  10.h3  , we make sure Black does not solve their opening problems by getting rid of the doubled f-pawns. }
8. O-O Bb7 9. d5
{ Black's king is temporarily stranded in the center. With d5! we are going to blast the center wide open and try to catch Black’s king right in the middle of the action. }
9... Na5 10. Bb5+ c6 11. dxc6 Bxc6
{ 11...Qxd1  runs into a brilliant in-between move  12.cxb7+!  Ke7  13.bxa8=Q  , when White resurrects the queen and gains extra material. }
12. Qe2 Bxb5 13. Qxb5+ Qd7 14. Qh5
{ With Black's wrecked kingside pawns, finding a safe spot for the king becomes a serious headache. Meanwhile, we will happily develop our bishop either through Bh6 or b3 followed by Bb2, and dominate the d-file with a timely Rad1. }
