{ Black first prepares castling before striking with  9...e5  , which is too early now and allows  10.Bb5!  ,  when Black's e5-pawn becomes rather vulnerable thanks to our pin on the knight. }
10. O-O O-O
{ 10...O-O-O  runs into  11.b4  and White's queenside attack is well underway. }
11. Re1
{ Black's pieces are all set for the ...e5 break, but it is White who has firm control of the e5-square. Our next move with Ne5 will stop the ...e5 break once and for all. The idea of Qe4 followed by Qh7# is not to be understated either. }
