[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Rubinstein 3...dxe4"]
[Black "Rubinstein 3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 Nd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ The Rubinstein Variation. By capturing on e4 early, Black concedes the center and grants White a space advantage, which Black hopes to neutralize with their solid setup. }
4. Nxe4
{ Compared to its Caro-Kann cousin, capturing on e4 early is less common, as ...e6 hampers the development of Black's light-squared bishop.   In the Caro-Kann, a line like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  dxe4  4.Nxe4  allows the bishop to develop with  4...Bf5  and  4...Nf6  .   Instead, here Black faces an interesting choice. Black must decide whether to realign the bishop along the a8-h1 diagonal directly, for example with ...Bd7-c6, or delay the bishop's development in favor of other pieces and only then develop it with ...b6 followed by ...Bb7.  Now that we recognize Black's main ideas, we should reflect on White's pluses. White's space advantage is undisputed, and our bishops are much more active than their counterparts. Furthermore, we retain the possibility of castling either side. }
4... Nd7 5. c3
{ I like this move, and we will shortly see its subtle point compared to the well-trodden path of  5.Nf3  Ngf6  6.Bd3  . It is worth noting that @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppn1ppp/4p3/8/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  will likely transpose to our main line. }
5... Ngf6
{ Black continues with the most natural response, challenging our centralized knight. }
6. Bd3 { The most natural development while protecting the knight. } 6... Nxe4
{ This capture is rather common as Black exchanges the knight to simplify the position and allows the other knight to occupy f6. Here we see a key point of c3/Bd3 instead of the conventional Nf3/Bd3. }
7. Bxe4 Nf6 8. Bc2
{ The bishop gets to retreat to c2 in one move, and freeing the d3-square for the queen for a formidable battery down the b1-h7 diagonal. It is now very risky for Black to continue autopiloting with ...Be7 and ...O-O. }
8... Be7
{ We will have a look at what happens when Black autopilots with the standard ...Be7 and ...O-O. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. Qd3
{ In just 10 moves, Black has already landed in an unpleasant position. The simple threat of Bg5xf6 and Qxh7# is rather worrisome. }
10... g6
{ What else?  10...h6  would only add fuel to the fire since after  11.g4+-  followed by g5, White's attack is unstoppable.   Also, a natural move like  10...b6  is well met by  11.Bg5  g6  12.h4  Bb7  13.O-O-O±  , when White keeps all the trumps. Even if Black tries to exchange more pieces with  13...Be4  14.Qe2  Bxc2  15.Kxc2  ,  the position remains difficult given the holes around the king on g8 and White's attacking prospects with Ne5 and h5. }
11. h4 { We are ready to destroy Black's kingside with h4-h5. } 11... b6 12. h5
Bb7 13. hxg6 fxg6
{ 13...hxg6  doesn't save the house from fire. After  14.Ne5  Bxg2  15.Nxg6  Bxh1  16.Nxe7+  Qxe7  17.Qg3+  ,  Black will lose the bishop on h1 with check and will also get mated once the dark-squared bishop lands on h6. }
14. Ng5
{ Besides a hanging pawn and a potential fork on e6, White has numerous threats with Nxh7 followed by Qxg6+, Qh3, and even Rxh7. Black's position was completely busted in Gong-De Vas, Perth 2020, a nice model game for how things can quickly go wrong for Black. }
