[Black "Rubinstein 3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 Nd7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ The Rubinstein Variation. By capturing on e4 early, Black concedes the center and grants White a space advantage, which Black hopes to neutralize with their solid setup. }
4. Nxe4
{ Compared to its Caro-Kann cousin, capturing on e4 early is less common, as ...e6 hampers the development of Black's light-squared bishop.   In the Caro-Kann, a line like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  dxe4  4.Nxe4  allows the bishop to develop with  4...Bf5  and  4...Nf6  .   Instead, here Black faces an interesting choice. Black must decide whether to realign the bishop along the a8-h1 diagonal directly, for example with ...Bd7-c6, or delay the bishop's development in favor of other pieces and only then develop it with ...b6 followed by ...Bb7.  Now that we recognize Black's main ideas, we should reflect on White's pluses. White's space advantage is undisputed, and our bishops are much more active than their counterparts. Furthermore, we retain the possibility of castling either side. }
4... Nd7 5. c3
{ I like this move, and we will shortly see its subtle point compared to the well-trodden path of  5.Nf3  Ngf6  6.Bd3  . It is worth noting that @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppn1ppp/4p3/8/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  will likely transpose to our main line. }
5... Ngf6
{ Black continues with the most natural response, challenging our centralized knight. }
6. Bd3 { The most natural development while protecting the knight. } 6... c5
{ Black has caught up with development and thus looks to strike in the center to undermine our d4-pawn. }
7. Nf3 cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ 8.cxd4  would simply gift Black a strong outpost  on d5. With  8.Nxd4  , we keep our pawn structure intact and the hopes of castling queenside alive. }
8... Be7 9. Qe2
{ As we have seen throughout the course, we should go for the maximum when Black fails to obstruct our development.   Rather than the conventional  9.O-O  , we will clear out our queenside pieces for an opposite-side castling, followed by initiating a kingside pawn storm  with g4 and h4. }
9... Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nf6 11. Bc2 a6 12. Bd2
{ 12.Bf4  might appear aggressive, but Black can force the bishop to retreat with  12...Nd5  . After  13.Bg3  , White still has a better position, but the bishop now gets in the way of the g-pawn, slowing down our typical plan of a kingside pawn storm following opposite-side castling.   12.Bg5  would give Black additional options to develop. For instance, after  12...Qa5  13.f4  Bd7  ,  castling queenside becomes an idea, while ...h6 is on the cards as well. }
12... Qc7 13. O-O-O
{ I may bore some readers, but I would like to spend a moment reflecting on the pawn structure here. After all, Philidor famously regarded pawns as the 'soul of chess'! White holds a 3 vs. 2 pawn majority on the queenside, which provides extra protection for our king. Despite an open c-file, it is difficult for Black to attack further without multiple moves of preparation.  In contrast, the 4 vs. 3 majority for Black on the kingside is less impressive. The extra e6-pawn obstructs the bishop on c8, does little to fend off our powerful bishop on c2, and allows us to freely launch our pawn storm with g4. In fact, you could almost make the argument that Black is better off without the e6-pawn! }
13... b5 14. Rhe1 Bb7
{ Unsurprisingly, it would be wise for Black to hold off on castling, especially with the kingside looking like a minefield. But hey, why wait for them to castle when we can make sure their king has nowhere to hide? }
15. Bg5
{ We will improve our bishop first, and open the scope for our rook on d1 before unleashing f2-f4-f5. Keep your eyes out for the stylish Nf5 too! }
15... Rd8 16. f4
{ Black has no good response to the incoming threat of f4-f5. Black's king will not find a safe place, castled or not. }
