[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Other 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Other 3rd Moves − 3...g5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 g5
{ It's a long shot, but imagine Black rolling out  3...g5!  Alright, I must admit that the chance of meeting this move is practically nil,  but do let the author for a moment indulge in his own creation. The move may seem insane, but it's got some sting, especially if it catches you off guard in a blitz game.  If you think about it, White's plan in the Tarrasch usually involves f2-f4 or Ng1-f3. Black's ...g7-g5 not only stops our f2-f4 on its track, but it also makes Ngf3 less appealing due to ...g5-g4. }
4. h4
{ We plan to get rid of that g5-pawn and exploit the squares around into weaknesses. }
4... gxh4 5. Ngf3
{ Now the knight can come to f3 without having to worry about ...g5-g4. } 5...
Be7
{ Otherwise, White will simply regain the pawn with an open h-file for the rook. }
6. Bd3 Nf6 7. e5 Ng4 8. Nxh4
{ Here, for a bit of flare, White opens up a discovered attack on the hanging knight on g4. }
8... h5
{ 8...Nxf2  may be tempting, but  9.Kxf2  Bxh4+  10.g3  Bg5  11.Qh5  exposes all the weaknesses Black revealed by overextending their pawns. We can start taking advantage of these weaknesses  with Nf3 and Bxh7. }
9. Ng6 { I wanted to dive into this fun line involving a queen sacrifice. }
9... fxg6 10. Qxg4
{ That's it! We sacrifice the queen to open the h-file for our rook. It is a bold move, but who doesn't like winning with a stunning sacrifice in chess? }
10... hxg4 11. Rxh8+ Bf8
{ At first glance, it appears that White has miscalculated due to the knight on d2 blocking what would be a devastating Bh6. Furthermore, with Bxg6+, it seems that the black king could easily escape via d7 to c6. }
12. Rh7 { We block Black's escape route and set up for a decisive Bxg6#. }
12... Be7 { A sad necessity to avoid the checkmate. } 13. Nb3
{ Opening the diagonal for the bishop. It is time to repeat Rh8+ and this time followed by Bh6. }
13... g5 { Sealing off the diagonal for our bishop to join the battle. } 14.
Be3
{ Just when it seems like White's fiery attack is slowing down, our second wave of attack is just beginning. It turns out Black has no good response against the slow threat of O-O-O and Rd1-h1-h8.   For instance, after  14...b6  15.O-O-O  Ba6  16.Rh8+  Bf8  17.Rdh1  , White is ready to sacrifice the rook  on h8 for the other rook to take its spot. Once again it is unlikely this novelty will get to see the light of the day over the board, but at least I hope the attack has been enjoyable to watch! }
