1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ A waiting move. Black simply develops the bishop and waits for White to show their hands. }
4. c3 c5 5. dxc5
{ Trying to gain a tempo by exploiting Black's early bishop move. } 5... Nf6
{ Black can throw in this move before recapturing on c5. } 6. e5
{ With Black's knight on f6, we will gladly push our e-pawn and enjoy our spatial advantage. A good rule of thumb to knowing whether the e4-e5 advance is strong is if:  it gains a valuable tempo by attacking the knight on f6; it allows us to establish our mighty center with f2-f4 in time. }
6... Nfd7 7. f4
{ We would like to play f4 given the opportunity. Despite the exchange on c5, our center remains solid, and we have freed up the d4-square for our minor pieces. }
7... Nxc5 { 7...Bxc5  will transpose to the upcoming 5...Bxc5 line. } 8. Ngf3
O-O 9. Nb3
{ We want to dislodge the knight from c5, allowing our bishop to go to d3. }
9... Nc6 10. Be3 b6
{ 10...Nxb3  gives White  access to the d3-square. Following  11.axb3  Bd7  12.Bd3  , White's pieces are on optimal squares. }
11. Qc2 { The queen stands well on c2, eyeing down the h7-pawn. } 11... Bb7 12.
O-O-O { Opposite-side castling promises a lot of fireworks here. } 12... a5 13.
Nbd4 a4 14. a3
{ With the queenside mostly locked up, we can turn our attention on Black's king. The position is double-edged, but I favor White. White has a clear plan of pawn storm followed by Nf3-g5, while it is difficult to give a concrete plan for Black. }
