1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 h6
{ An interesting move. Like  3...Be7  , Black also chooses to wait and  prepare ...c5. }
4. c3
{ In the past, when an unusual move appeared on the board, it was expected to be refuted quickly. However, with modern engines, even the oddest moves are harder to crack.   The key to combating these surprises is to steer the game into lines where such waiting moves become less useful. For example, after  4.Ngf3  Nf6  5.e5  Nfd7  6.Bd3  c5  7.c3  Nc6  8.O-O  g5!?  , Black makes effective use of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...h6  . }
4... c5 5. exd5 Qxd5
{ Avoiding the IQP position. But here ...h6 is not the most useful move and White can gain multiple tempi on Black's queen. }
6. Ngf3 cxd4 7. Bc4 Qd6
{ 7...Qh5  invites an interesting pawn sacrifice with  8.Ne4  . After  8...dxc3  9.O-O  Nd7  10.Re1  , Black must tread carefully, as their king remains stranded in the center. }
8. Nxd4 Nf6 9. Qe2 a6
{ An important prophylactic move for Black to prepare ...Nc6. Instead,  9...Nc6  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Ne4  Nxe4  12.Qxe4  leaves White in full control with the bishops soon taking over the board. }
10. N2f3 Nc6 11. Be3
{ While Black has been forced to spend moves on ...a6 and ...h6, White enjoys a harmonious development and is ready to speed up the game with O-O-O, g3, and Bf4. }
