{ 7.e5  is potentially premature since Black has  7...Ng4!  , highlighting the fact that White has not castled yet  by targeting f2 and e5. After  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Qe2  Qc7  , White is finding it hard to hold onto  the e5-pawn since  10.Re1  runs into the nasty  10...Bxf2+  . }
7... dxe4 { Black can take this opportunity to simplify the position. } 8. Nxe4
Nxe4 9. Bxe4 Qxd1 10. Rxd1
{ Following the exchange of queens, the position appears to have stabilized, but this has not relieved Black's difficult position. White is clearly ahead in development and can look to restrict Black's queenside pieces from coming out. }
10... O-O
{ 10...Nd7  ,  preparing for ...Nf6 to drive our e4-bishop back is met with the brilliant  11.Ne1!  We plan to regroup the knight  to d3, and in the event of  11...Nf6  12.Bf3  , it is difficult to see how Black manages to get the light-squared bishop out while protecting  the b7-pawn. }
11. Ne5 { Restricting Black's pieces seems to be the name of the game now. }
11... f6 { It is hard to suggest something else at this point. } 12. Nc4 Nc6
13. Be3 Bxe3 14. fxe3
{ Black's position has not improved over the last few moves, as the bishop on c8 is still struggling to make an impact. Meanwhile, White is ready to continue in full force with Nb6, Rd6, and Rad1. }
