1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 a6
{ Another waiting move. Black's ...a6 move is useful in eliminating potential Bb5+ business, especially when preparing for ...c5. }
4. Bd3 c5 5. dxc5
{ Although it is generally preferable to capture on c5 after Black has moved their dark-squared bishop, here we lack useful moves to delay this capture.   For instance  5.c3  cxd4  6.cxd4  dxe4  leaves White with a  weak IQP on d4, whereas  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pp4/3PP3/3B4/PPPN1PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq c6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Ngf3  c4  results in our bishop  losing its crucial d3-square. Instead, capturing on c5 immediately allows us a straightforward development route. }
5... Bxc5 6. Ngf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Qe2
{ 8.e5  is again premature, as Black has again  8...Ng4!  at their disposal. After  9.Qe2  Qc7  , it is difficult to hold  onto the e5-pawn since the natural  10.Re1  run into the nasty  10...Bxf2+  . }
8... O-O 9. e5
{ With White's king safely castled and the e-pawn reinforced by the queen on e2, this advance makes much more sense. }
9... Nd7
{ Now that White has castled,  9...Ng4  can be effectively countered by  10.h3  , compelling the knight to make a big decision. The knight could either retreat to the  awkward h6-square or capture on f2, giving White two minor pieces for a rook and a pawn.  While this trade is generally considered even in terms of material value @@StartBracket@@both at 6 points@@EndBracket@@, the two minor pieces are usually preferred during the middlegame thanks to their greater control over the board. }
10. Nb3 Ba7 11. Bxh7+
{ The perfect opportunity for a classic Greek Gift sacrifice − a theme every chess player should familiarize themselves with. Black's knights are far from the king and the e5-pawn restricts the knight from defending with ...Nf6. Although this sacrifice doesn't win the game outright, Black must defend with utmost precision or risk getting crushed.   Playing the position slow with  11.Bf4  is of course fine too. After  11...f6  , we have on our hands a much slower and more positional battle for the center. }
11... Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg6
{ The king chooses to come out and brave the storm.   12...Kg8  is usually the most natural reaction but after  13.Qh5  , Black must part with their queen or get mated  on h7. For instance  13...Re8?  14.Qxf7+  Kh8  15.Qh5+  Kg8  16.Qh7+  Kf8  17.Qh8+  Ke7  18.Qxg7#  is a brutal finish. }
13. Qd3+
{ The king is not exactly safe on g6, and we are highlighting that with Qd3+ followed by Qg3. }
13... f5 14. Qg3
{ Threatening a devastating discovered check on e6, winning the black queen. }
14... Qe7
{ The only move that doesn't lose outright. Instead,  14...Qe8  15.Nxe6+  Kf7  16.Nc7  forks the queen and  rook on a8. }
15. Re1 Rh8 16. Bf4
{ Black's king is stuck helplessly on g6. Just to get a glimpse of the fun or chaos, Stockfish likes the idea of  16...Rh5  17.Nxe6+  Kh7  18.Nc7  g5  19.Qf3  Rh6  20.e6  Nc5  21.Nxd5  Qg7  22.Be3  ,  when the 3400-rated silicon beast announces a dead equal 0.00 evaluation in absolute cold-blood fashion. I am sure any human player playing Black here must feel exactly the same... }
