1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6
{ At first, this seems odd and almost counterintuitive. Black voluntarily blocks their own c-pawn, while ...c7-c5 in most positions in the French constitutes Black's most natural and effective counterplay.  Still, this move caught the attention of one of the greatest opening innovators of all time, Aron Nimzowitsch, who played it from time to time. So there is more than meets the eye and this move is not to be overlooked. }
4. Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nd7
{ Black has provoked the e5 advance and prepares for counterplay with ...f6. }
6. c3 f6 7. Bb5
{ A dangerous move. The bishop temporarily ties Black's knights down to the king, hindering Black's counterplay. In the long run, Black will be able to untangle with ...Be7 and ...O-O, but by then White would have also completed development. Additionally, the bishop can also be retreated to d3 later to exert pressure on Black's kingside. }
7... fxe5 8. dxe5 Be7 9. O-O
{ 9.Nd4  is also quite interesting. As this is a sideline, I've chosen not to include it as an alternative. But the point is that  9...Ndxe5  runs into  10.Qh5+  Kf8  11.f4  Nxd4  12.fxe5  Nf5  13.Nf3  and Black's king is certainly attracting some unwanted attention. }
9... O-O 10. Re1
{ If Black's pawn is on c5 instead of c7, Black would already be fine, if not slightly better with the queenside play. Instead, here Black has little to show for 3...Nc6, and instead must spend additional moves moving the knight to achieve ...c5. Black must also be cautious of potential Re1-e3-h3 and Qd1-h5 ideas. }
10... Qe8
{ Covering the e8-h5 diagonal and preparing either ...Qg6 or ...Qh5. } 11. Nd4
{ We can take advantage of the queen coming on e8 tactically. The pawn on e5 is immune since  11...Ncxe5  runs into  12.Rxe5!  c6  13.Re1  cxb5  14.Nxe6  and the hanging rook on f8 combined with the threat of fork on c7 means that Black's position collapses. }
11... Nxd4 12. cxd4 c5 13. Nf3 c4
{ Delaying White's bishop on b5 its optimal repositioning on the b1-h7 diagonal. }
14. Ba4 Qh5 15. Re3
{ A very powerful rook lift! Over the next few moves, White aims to vacate the 3rd rank for the rook to join the party.   One stylish example is  15...a6  16.Bc2  b5  17.Qe1  Nb6  18.Ng5!  , when both  18...Bxg5  and  18...Qxg5  run into  19.Rh3  , winning the queen. }
