1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ndf3 Qb6 8. a3
{ 8.h4!  is recommended in our repertoire. However, the position will soon  transpose with the inclusion of h4 and ...f6. }
8... a5 9. b3 Be7 10. h4 f6 11. Bd3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nf8
{ With  12...Nf8  , Black is hoping to hold the kingside while  preparing for ...Na7, ...Bd7-b5, and ...Rc8, mobilizing the queenside pieces. It's an interesting concept, but time is a luxury in this position. }
13. Ne2 Bd7 14. Nc3
{ The knight rushes to a4, where it will force Black's queen to retreat and prepare a potential jump to c5. Black still has a lot of questions to be solved. }
14... Na7 15. Na4 Qc7 16. Bb2 Bb5 17. Rc1 Qd8 18. Bxb5+ Nxb5 19. Qe2 Na7
{ 19...Nxa3  is too greedy and deserves to be punished. After  20.O-O  , it is not clear how Black's knight can ever get out. }
20. exf6
{ It would have been a bit difficult to break down Black's defense if they were in time to play ...f5. Now Black's king finds itself stuck in the center, with no clear ways to escape. }
20... gxf6 21. O-O Kf7 22. Nc5 h5
{ A sad necessity, or else Ng5+ & Qh5+ will come with devastating effect. } 23.
f5 exf5 24. Qd3 b6 25. Na6 Rh7
{ Black's position is already in disarray, but with  25...Rh7?  , Black finally crumbles under pressure.  25...Kg7  is arguably more tenacious. }
26. Qxf5 Nb5 27. Ng5+ Kg7 28. Nxh7 Nxh7 29. Rf3 Bd6
{ 29...Rxa6?  would run into  30.Rg3+  Kh8  31.Rc8  , winning the queen and the game. }
30. a4 Na7 31. Qxh5 Nc8 32. Rfc3 Ne7 33. Qg4+ Kh8 34. Nc7 f5 35. Qh5 Rc8 36.
Ne6 Qg8 37. Rxc8 Nxc8 38. Ng5
{ Black resigned. One of my best games of the tournament, which helped me reclaim my title as the WA State Champion! }
