[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Anatoly Karpov − Wolfgang Uhlmann, Madrid 1973"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ The French Tarrasch was a long-time favorite of the 12th World Champion Anatoly Karpov, who played it with great success. His positional and solid playing style makes him a formidable opponent, and his expertise in playing against the isolated pawn is unparalleled, where a single slip from the opponent can be punished. This is a model game where Karpov had a slight edge and never let it go. }
1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
O-O Ne7 9. Nb3 Bd6 10. Bg5
{ 10.c3  followed by Bd3 is our repertoire recommendation. } 10... O-O 11. Bh4
Bg4 12. Be2 Bh5 13. Re1 Qb6 14. Nfd4
{ White manages to occupy the important d4-outpost, but Black's position remains rock solid. }
14... Bg6 15. c3 Rfe8 16. Bf1 Be4 17. Bg3 Bxg3 18. hxg3 a5 19. a4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4
Nc6
{ Capturing the b2-pawn with  20...Qxb2?  is rather greedy. After  21.Nb5!  , Black is in big trouble. They cannot defend against the  dual threat of Nc7, forking the rooks, and Re2, trapping Black's queen. }
21. Bb5 Red8 22. g4 Nxd4 23. Qxd4 Qxd4 24. cxd4
{ Despite almost having a symmetrical pawn structure with the isolated d-pawns, Karpov has transformed his advantage in the form of a superior light-squared bishop, and the dangerous idea of infiltrating the open e-file with f3 and Re7. }
24... Rac8 25. f3 Bg6 26. Re7 b6 27. Rae1 h6 28. Rb7
{ Despite the material balance, it is becoming increasingly difficult for Black to find proactive moves. It is a fine display of Karpov's 'boa constrictor' playing style, suffocating the opponent's play gradually. }
28... Rd6 29. Ree7 h5 30. gxh5 Bxh5 31. g4 Bg6 32. f4 Rc1+ 33. Kf2 Rc2+ 34. Ke3
Be4 35. Rxf7 Rg6 36. g5 Kh7 37. Rfe7 Rxb2 38. Be8 Rb3+ 39. Ke2 Rb2+ 40. Ke1 Rd6
41. Rxg7+ Kh8 42. Rge7
{ Black resigned. One must wonder where Black all went wrong. } *

