[Black "Vitaly Tseshkovsky − Igor Glek, Philadelphia 1990"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ As I mentioned in the repertoire, @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp3ppp/3qpn2/8/2BN4/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bd7!?  likely represents Black's most assertive attempt in the Tarrasch after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pP4/3P4/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qxd5  . Instead of shying away from this fact, I would like to show a game where Black succeeds in turning the table. Perhaps this will enable us to better appreciate the line and improve on White's play. }
1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Ngf3 cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O Nf6 8.
Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7
{ Black voluntarily castles on the opposite side and plans to initiate a dangerous attack with ...h5 and ...Ng4. }
11. b3 O-O-O 12. Bb2 Qc7 13. Qe2 h5 14. Nf3 Ng4 15. Rad1 Bd6 16. h3
{ Precision is key here. My recommendation for White is an interesting exchange sacrifice with  16.Rxd6  Qxd6  17.Rd1!  , and only after  17...Qc7  play  18.h3  , driving back Black's knight. For the exchange, White gains long-term compensation with active pieces. For instance  18...Nf6  19.Be5  Qb6  20.Ng5  , when  White has a nice initiative with Rd6 and a4 incoming to gradually improve the position. }
16... Bc6 17. Rxd6
{ White is still doing okay after  17.Rfe1  , but now the game takes a turn for the worse, and Black gains a dangerous attack. }
17... Qxd6 18. hxg4
{ Gaining two minor pieces for the rook. But in reality, with Black's queen and bishop pointing at the king, White really cannot afford to open the h-file. }
18... hxg4 19. Ne5 Rh4
{ With Black's rooks ready to double on the h-file, White is in serious trouble. }
20. Nxg4 Rdh8 21. f3 Qg3
{ This move essentially seals White's fate, the king now cannot escape. } 22.
Bxe6+ fxe6 23. Qxe6+ Bd7 24. Qc4+ Kd8
{ Without a good way to stop ...Rh1#, White resigned. } *

