1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. c3 Be7 7. Nf3 Nxe4 8.
Bxe4 Nf6 9. Bc2 O-O
{ It is rather easy for Black to autopilot in the French and castle kingside, but truth be told sometimes Black can castle straight into their doom.   9...c5  is better, as Black should keep the king in the center for as long as possible. After  10.Be3  Qc7  11.dxc5  Bxc5  12.Bxc5  Qxc5  13.Qe2  , White prepares to castle queenside with good attacking prospects, although the position remains double-edged. }
10. Qd3
{ The bishop and queen battery will haunt Black's king for the rest of the game. }
10... g6 11. h4
{ The plan is simple. Push the h-pawn, open the kingside, and checkmate! Black's position is already critical. }
11... b6 12. h5 Bb7 13. hxg6 fxg6
{ 13...hxg6  doesn't save the house from fire. After  14.Ne5  Bxg2  15.Nxg6  Bxh1  16.Nxe7+  Qxe7  17.Qg3+  ,  Black will lose the bishop on h1 with check and will also get mated once the dark-squared bishop lands on h6. }
14. Ng5 Qe8 15. Qh3 Nh5 16. Qxe6+ Kg7 17. Nxh7
{ Simple and effective. During the game, I was also extremely tempted by the stunning combination after  17.Rxh5?  gxh5??  18.Qh6+!!  Kxh6  19.Ne6+  Rf4  20.Bxf4+  Bg5  21.Bxg5#  . Sadly Black does have @@StartFEN@@r3qr2/pbp1b1kp/1p2Q1p1/6NR/3P4/2P5/PPB2PP1/R1B1K3 b Q - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Bxg5  , when it is White who is in big trouble. }
17... Bc8 18. Qe5+ Bf6 19. Nxf6 Qxe5+ 20. dxe5
{ White wins a piece with the attack still raging ahead. } 20... Rh8 21. Bg5
Bb7 22. O-O-O Bc6 23. g4 Bxh1 24. Rd7+ Kf8 25. gxh5
{ Black finally throws in the towel; the threat of e6/Bxg6 and Rf7# is simply too much to handle. }
